00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:29.120
PROFESSOR: OK, so let's
situate ourselves where we are.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:31.550
So we're starting to really
make a lot of progress

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:33.860
here, moving in the V model.

00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:38.240
Today's topic is session
five: tradespace exploration,

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:40.220
concept selection, and PDR--

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:41.440
preliminary design review.

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:46.690
So there's a lot to
talk about, and I'm

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:48.660
going to go relatively
quickly through this.

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:51.880
So, first I want to talk
about decision analysis.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:55.960
Fundamentally, when
you come up for PDR,

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:59.470
you have to make a big decision
which is, what concept are you

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:00.220
going for?

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:02.344
What is your system
architecture?

00:01:02.344 --> 00:01:03.260
That's a big decision.

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:04.720
You don't have all
the details yet.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:07.120
The design is not
fully done, but you've

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:08.980
chosen your key architecture.

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:10.720
That's a big
decision, and there's

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:13.510
a whole branch of research
and science called

00:01:13.510 --> 00:01:14.790
decision analysis.

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:17.360
So I want to tell
you about that.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:20.650
Talk about some of the issues
in concept selection, and then

00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:22.690
give you some tools
for doing that

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:24.550
in a kind of organized way.

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:25.720
There's a couple of--

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:29.830
what I would say, simple methods
Pugh matrix and multi-attribute

00:01:29.830 --> 00:01:31.060
utility--

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:33.520
that are relatively, I
think, straightforward.

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:37.810
And then there's a bit more
advanced concept called

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:39.940
non-dominance--

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:44.050
Pareto frontiers, getting into
multi-objective optimization.

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:47.020
And so, at a minimum, when
you choose your concept,

00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:49.630
you want to choose a
non-dominated concept.

00:01:49.630 --> 00:01:51.530
And I'll explain
what that means.

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.750
And then we'll close with
discussing what is a PDR?

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:57.160
What do you do with the PDR?

00:01:57.160 --> 00:01:59.560
What's the purpose of it?

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:04.320
So, here is another way to
explain essentially the flow

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:08.880
of things as we come up to PDR.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:11.400
So the way you can
think of it as, you

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:12.960
start with a need, right?

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.110
And your requirements.

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:17.590
That's-- we've talked
about that before.

00:02:17.590 --> 00:02:19.270
And then you have
this creative phase,

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:20.950
which we talked about
last time, right?

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:24.210
You come up with a lot of
ideas, a lot of concepts,

00:02:24.210 --> 00:02:28.500
and the funnel that you
see here is going up.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:30.730
So each of these shapes here--

00:02:30.730 --> 00:02:32.850
the circle, the triangle--

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:35.640
they're meant to represent
fundamentally different

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:37.410
concepts, different
architecture,

00:02:37.410 --> 00:02:39.780
different way of satisfying
the requirements.

00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:42.750
And so there's a lot of
different things you can do,

00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:44.340
and the funnel opens up.

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:48.570
This is sort of the size
of options or alternatives

00:02:48.570 --> 00:02:49.890
you're considering.

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:53.730
And then you have
to filter this down.

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:56.000
In the end, you can only
build one system, right?

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.320
You have to choose
one architecture.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:01.480
And this filtering down
happens typically in two steps.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:04.770
One is what we call
concept screening, which

00:03:04.770 --> 00:03:07.380
is more qualitative.

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:10.260
And then the actual
concept selection

00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:13.330
is more quantitative, based
on models, based on data,

00:03:13.330 --> 00:03:15.990
based on metrics.

00:03:15.990 --> 00:03:17.350
And then you arrive at PDR.

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:20.250
So in this sort of
simplified view,

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:25.250
we've chosen the
square as our concept.

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:27.630
And we've made that
decision by looking

00:03:27.630 --> 00:03:29.620
at these different metrics.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:33.580
So you can see that
on this graphic here,

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:35.510
we have metric one, metric two--

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:37.830
you can see the triangle
is dominated, right?

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:40.020
The triangle doesn't
do as well if we

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.470
want to maximize
metric one and two,

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:44.790
so it wouldn't make sense
to choose the triangle.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:50.070
But the circle and the square--

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.890
circle does better on
metric two, but less well

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:53.820
on metric one.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:56.860
The square does better on
metric one, not quite as well--

00:03:56.860 --> 00:03:58.870
and they crossover
at some point.

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:01.740
So, whatever-- how you weigh
this in decision making,

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:03.120
the decision is made.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:04.710
We're going to go
for the square.

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:06.180
That's our concept.

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:10.620
And then you move to the
actual system design, post-PDR,

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:12.750
which is all the details.

00:04:12.750 --> 00:04:16.350
So we're expanding the box
now, the square, and designing

00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:17.790
all the details within--

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:21.300
the structure, the avionics,
the software, the controls.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:25.080
And that's design
modeling and optimization.

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:28.260
And so here I'm showing you
metric three, which is maybe

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:32.250
another metric, and then
design variable x1, which

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:35.190
is some pretty detailed
decision that you

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:37.230
make within that
concept, and you're

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:40.470
looking for the optimal, in this
case, minimizing metric three.

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:41.970
It's this point here.

00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:43.470
And then that gives
you your-- and I

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:46.560
put this deliberately in
quotes-- optimal design.

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:49.680
That's what you show at the CDR,
and the critical design review,

00:04:49.680 --> 00:04:51.490
and that's what
you go and build.

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:56.650
So that's roughly the
flow of decision making.

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:58.020
Any question about that?

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.980
That general flow?

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:02.280
So what we'll talk about
today is essentially

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:05.550
this portion here,
concept screening

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:08.420
and concept selection.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:13.110
So, since you make a decision,
what is decision analysis?

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:14.900
So decision
analysis, in general,

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:18.350
is methods and tools
for ranking and choosing

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:22.280
among competing alternatives
or courses of action.

00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:24.080
And I just want to make--

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:26.270
the word alternative.

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:29.360
A lot of people use the
word option and alternative

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:31.670
sort of as synonyms.

00:05:31.670 --> 00:05:32.431
They're not.

00:05:32.431 --> 00:05:32.930
OK?

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:34.010
They're not.

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:36.360
Options and alternatives
are not the same thing.

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:43.250
An alternative means if I choose
A, I can't choose B and C.

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:46.640
But the fact that you've
chosen A, or the square,

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:50.870
or whatever your concept is,
means that you cannot choose

00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:52.310
the other ones.

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:56.885
An option means, well
given that I've chosen A,

00:05:56.885 --> 00:06:00.350
I could also add something
on top of A, right?

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:02.720
It's kind of like if you
were buying a new car,

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:05.310
are you going to get the
winter package or not?

00:06:05.310 --> 00:06:09.580
That's an option, but you've
chosen a particular vehicle.

00:06:09.580 --> 00:06:11.390
So, that's important.

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:16.070
So alternatives are mutually
exclusive choices or courses

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:16.710
of action.

00:06:16.710 --> 00:06:18.230
So you need the
alternatives, those

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:21.670
are the components-- four
components of a decision.

00:06:21.670 --> 00:06:26.570
You need criteria, which means
how are you going to evaluate

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:28.610
and compare the alternatives?

00:06:28.610 --> 00:06:30.350
Then you need value judgments.

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:33.980
You now apply the criteria
to the alternatives

00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:36.140
to compare them,
and then finally you

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:37.910
need a decision
maker, which is either

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:41.120
an individual or a
group with preferences

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:42.980
to then make the choice.

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:46.280
Those are the four ingredients
of decision analysis.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:49.760
And if we show this somewhat
graphically-- so here's

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:51.170
our alternatives.

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:55.310
We can do A, B, or C.
The criteria in this case

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:57.760
are cost, performance, and risk.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:02.720
Then we basically evaluate,
in this case, option

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:06.470
or alternative A, I should
say, for cost, for performance,

00:07:06.470 --> 00:07:07.370
for risk.

00:07:07.370 --> 00:07:10.880
And this gives us
some score or number,

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:12.560
and then we need
to figure out a way

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:16.700
to combine this to
rank the alternatives.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:18.650
And when it comes
to ranking, there's

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.680
a distinction between what's
known as an ordinal scale

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:23.540
and a cardinal scale.

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:27.410
So in an ordinal ranking all
you really care about and do

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:30.390
is say, what's the best
choice, the second best choice,

00:07:30.390 --> 00:07:31.350
and the third choice.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:33.980
You ordered the alternative.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:37.580
But you don't know in an ordinal
ranking or ordinal scale,

00:07:37.580 --> 00:07:40.910
whether one and two
are really close,

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:45.530
and then there's a big
gap between two and three.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:47.660
You don't know that, and
you don't really care.

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:50.060
All you want is the rank order.

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:52.780
When you put things
on a cardinal scale--

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:54.830
so this is a continuous line--

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:58.220
you actually get, in a
sense, both the order

00:07:58.220 --> 00:08:00.920
but you also see how close
the alternatives are.

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:05.350
So that's a cardinal scale as
opposed to an ordinal scale.

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:06.500
OK?

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.000
So-- yes?

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:09.129
Please.

00:08:09.129 --> 00:08:11.420
AUDIENCE: How do you get a
discrete value for something

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:13.862
like risk or
something like that?

00:08:13.862 --> 00:08:15.320
And especially in
an ordinal scale,

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:17.778
if you have two things that
are really close to each other,

00:08:17.778 --> 00:08:20.774
but the risk is kind of a
blurry region, how do you--

00:08:20.774 --> 00:08:22.940
PROFESSOR: So then they
would be equivalent in terms

00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:24.500
of that criterion.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:28.020
And you can actually
have ties, right?

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:30.540
You can have alternatives
that are tied.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:32.240
And I'll talk
about-- this is one

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:33.830
of the issues in
concept selection

00:08:33.830 --> 00:08:35.929
is, how do you do tie breaking?

00:08:35.929 --> 00:08:37.280
Good question.

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:38.900
Any questions at EPFL?

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:40.890
I know this is very abstract.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:44.210
But fundamentally,
that's what we do.

00:08:44.210 --> 00:08:48.370
Any questions over there?

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:50.335
Is it clear?

00:08:50.335 --> 00:08:51.627
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:08:51.627 --> 00:08:52.210
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:53.290
Good.

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:55.670
So let's keep moving.

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:56.680
So what are the issues?

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:59.557
I think that's-- so
multiple criteria,

00:08:59.557 --> 00:09:00.640
how do you deal with them?

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:03.850
We usually have multiple
criteria and how do we--

00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:06.970
and eventually, when you
make a decision, when

00:09:06.970 --> 00:09:08.800
you pick a concept,
you're somehow

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:13.630
combining these criteria
into a single measure,

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:15.820
whether you're doing
that explicitly or not.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:18.260
So how do you deal with
these multiple criteria?

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:19.880
We'll talk about that.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:21.850
Here's the point
that you brought up.

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:23.110
What if there's ties?

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:24.970
How do you break them?

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:28.540
Group decision making versus
individual decision making--

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:30.910
who gets to really
make the decision?

00:09:30.910 --> 00:09:31.780
Right?

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:34.570
And this relates to the
stakeholder analysis.

00:09:34.570 --> 00:09:38.230
Who has the power to make
the decision in the end?

00:09:38.230 --> 00:09:42.820
And then uncertainty-- did
we choose the right criteria?

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:46.520
Did we evaluate each
option properly?

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:49.540
And then the big one
is are the the best

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:51.550
alternatives represented?

00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:54.220
So you can choose
among A, B, and C,

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:57.610
but maybe there's this much,
much better architecture

00:09:57.610 --> 00:10:01.870
concept D out there, but
it's not in the decision set.

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:04.300
Because it didn't--
nobody thought of it,

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:07.690
or some other thing happened,
and it didn't come up

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:09.140
in concept generation.

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:09.640
Right?

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:11.742
So there's a lot
of uncertainties

00:10:11.742 --> 00:10:12.700
when you're doing this.

00:10:12.700 --> 00:10:15.440
So you have to be aware of it.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:19.900
So let me talk about two--

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:23.140
again, quote, end
quote-- "simple methods"

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:24.640
for doing concept selection.

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:27.400
The first one is
called Pugh matrix,

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:30.440
and then I'll talk
about utility analysis.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:34.520
So the Pugh matrix, essentially,
is a very discrete method.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:39.670
It uses essentially plus, zero,
and minus to score alternatives

00:10:39.670 --> 00:10:41.440
relative to a datum.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:45.950
A datum is a reference decision,
a reference architecture.

00:10:45.950 --> 00:10:48.600
And this is named
after Stuart Pugh,

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:55.060
who is a British professor
of design, essentially.

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:58.360
And it's a very simple method.

00:10:58.360 --> 00:11:00.820
And it's used extensively.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:04.820
It does have some pitfalls, as
well, but it's very well known.

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:07.470
So Pugh matrix

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:11.830
And then the second one is
called utility analysis.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:15.670
So it essentially
maps all the criteria

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:20.440
to a dimensionless utility,
this is between zero and one.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:23.240
So zero is a completely
useless system.

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:25.090
It has zero utility.

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:28.360
And one is a system that
has perfect utility.

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:30.010
It can't really be improved.

00:11:30.010 --> 00:11:32.560
You could try to improve
it but your satisfaction

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:34.960
would not increase, OK?

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:39.160
And this has very deep
mathematical theory,

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:44.360
particularly the Von
Neumann and Morgenstern

00:11:44.360 --> 00:11:51.030
utility that was
basically developed

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:53.000
in the mid-twentieth century.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.420
Anybody seen the movie
A Beautiful Mind?

00:11:57.420 --> 00:11:57.920
Yeah?

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:01.460
What is is A
Beautiful Mind about?

00:12:07.412 --> 00:12:09.520
AUDIENCE: It's about John--

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:13.510
mathematician John Nash who's
a mathematician who won--

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:18.400
I forget exactly what
prize he had won.

00:12:22.684 --> 00:12:24.100
PROFESSOR: He won
the Nobel Prize.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:25.475
AUDIENCE: Was it
the Nobel Prize?

00:12:25.475 --> 00:12:26.300
OK.

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:27.550
AUDIENCE: Founded game theory.

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:28.383
PROFESSOR: For what?

00:12:28.383 --> 00:12:29.590
For game theory, right.

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:33.040
And so one of
Nash's contributions

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:35.120
was the idea of a
Nash equilibrium.

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:38.110
So we have multiple
decision makers in gaming,

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:40.460
and the question is--

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:42.520
you have your current
strategy, but is there

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:44.410
a better move you could make?

00:12:44.410 --> 00:12:47.290
And if you could make
a better move that

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:52.280
improves your satisfaction,
or your utility,

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:56.590
but by doing this, you decrease
somebody else's utility,

00:12:56.590 --> 00:12:58.480
you may not go there.

00:12:58.480 --> 00:13:00.450
So if you reach a
Nash equilibrium,

00:13:00.450 --> 00:13:02.980
that means that everybody
believes that this

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:05.140
is the best they can achieve.

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:06.740
And how do you measure that?

00:13:06.740 --> 00:13:12.130
Well Nash actually developed
his Nash equilibrium and game

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:18.880
theory building upon theories
of Von Neumann and Morgenstern.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:21.560
So there's a very
deep theory behind it.

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:23.450
I'm not going to go
very deep into it,

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:29.010
but so you know that there's
a lot behind utility analysis.

00:13:29.010 --> 00:13:33.970
OK, so let me just talk
you through the basic steps

00:13:33.970 --> 00:13:35.920
for doing a Pugh
matrix analysis.

00:13:35.920 --> 00:13:38.500
And I'll show you a
very simple example.

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:41.290
First step, you choose
or develop the criteria

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:43.430
for comparison.

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:45.530
So, what's important?

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:47.470
How are we going to decide this?

00:13:47.470 --> 00:13:48.610
Selection.

00:13:48.610 --> 00:13:50.140
And obviously this
should be based

00:13:50.140 --> 00:13:53.990
on a set of system
requirements and goals.

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:57.710
Now, there are two
flavors of requirements.

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:01.390
Remember, what-- let's
ask here at EPFL.

00:14:01.390 --> 00:14:04.330
You remember the two
flavors of requirements?

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:07.921
What were the two
flavors of requirements?

00:14:07.921 --> 00:14:19.712
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:19.712 --> 00:14:21.920
PROFESSOR: I mean, there's
actually six types, right?

00:14:21.920 --> 00:14:24.100
There's functional requirements.

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:26.850
There is constraints.

00:14:26.850 --> 00:14:31.360
There's interface
requirements, and so forth.

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:34.180
What I'm trying to get at
is there are requirements

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.010
that use shall
statements and then

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:39.310
there's requirements that
use should statements, right?

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:41.410
So the shall
statements are what?

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:43.195
What do the shell
statements imply?

00:14:47.304 --> 00:14:50.912
AUDIENCE: So basically, for
the shall, it's compulsory,

00:14:50.912 --> 00:14:55.180
and for should, it's
a goal of the system.

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:56.200
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:56.980
Exactly.

00:14:56.980 --> 00:15:00.280
So, in some sense,
the shall state--

00:15:00.280 --> 00:15:03.520
the criteria associated
with shall statements

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:07.960
don't necessarily make the best
criteria for the Pugh matrix,

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:12.130
because by definition, the
concepts that you're evaluating

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:14.770
should all satisfy
the shall statements.

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:19.030
Because if they don't, they're
essentially infeasible, right?

00:15:19.030 --> 00:15:23.710
And you shouldn't select
among them in the first place.

00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:27.430
So architectures, or
concepts, or alternatives

00:15:27.430 --> 00:15:35.340
that violate shall requirements
do not satisfy the must

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:37.120
have requirements.

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:40.570
And you shouldn't-- so you
shouldn't use criteria that are

00:15:40.570 --> 00:15:42.610
associated with
hard constraints.

00:15:42.610 --> 00:15:44.770
That's what I'm trying to say.

00:15:44.770 --> 00:15:46.840
Now the requirements
that are associated with

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:51.400
should statements, those are
good criteria for this Pugh

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.920
matrix, because the degree
to which you satisfy this,

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:57.020
the goals are somewhat variable.

00:15:57.020 --> 00:15:59.540
Therefore, you can then
compare amongst alternatives.

00:15:59.540 --> 00:16:00.400
OK?

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:01.330
So that's number one.

00:16:01.330 --> 00:16:05.110
Number two-- thank
you, that was good--

00:16:05.110 --> 00:16:07.160
select the alternatives
to be compared.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:11.080
So that those are coming out
of concept generation and one

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:16.360
little bit tricky aspect here
is when you're putting together

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:19.780
the alternatives, the
concepts to be selected from,

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:21.790
they should be represented
at a similar level

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:24.070
of detail of abstraction.

00:16:24.070 --> 00:16:28.840
It is not good to have one
concept that's really detailed,

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:30.640
and you know a lot
about it, and often it's

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:33.640
kind of an existing system or
something you've done before,

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:38.440
and then there's this other
concept that is very fuzzy.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:41.560
Why shouldn't you compare
something very detailed

00:16:41.560 --> 00:16:45.820
with something very,
very poorly defined?

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:49.090
Why do you think that's
not a good practice?

00:16:49.090 --> 00:16:50.780
What do you guys think here?

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:52.050
Yes.

00:16:52.050 --> 00:16:53.440
AUDIENCE: Is it like--

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:55.050
it's not fair, because--

00:16:55.050 --> 00:16:56.050
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:59.320
It's a fairness issue,
and because the concepts

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.550
that are poorly
defined often, you're

00:17:02.550 --> 00:17:04.060
too optimistic about them.

00:17:04.060 --> 00:17:05.560
That's sort of the typical--

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:09.099
this looks really
good, very promising,

00:17:09.099 --> 00:17:11.500
but it looks very
promising because it's

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:13.319
kind of ill-defined.

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:15.319
So that's important.

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:17.349
Try to represent
all the concepts

00:17:17.349 --> 00:17:19.510
at about the same
level of detail

00:17:19.510 --> 00:17:21.010
when you make the comparison.

00:17:21.010 --> 00:17:22.960
That's number two.

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:26.440
Number three-- you actually
go through and generate

00:17:26.440 --> 00:17:27.880
the scores.

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:30.280
And the key thing
here-- this is maybe

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:32.560
the most important thing
about the Pugh matrix

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:36.250
is you always use a datum.

00:17:36.250 --> 00:17:40.330
The datum is a reference--
one of the alternatives

00:17:40.330 --> 00:17:43.220
that you're going to
compare is your reference.

00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:47.560
So what you do is you always
compare every other alternative

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:51.550
in the set against the datum,
and you say for each criterion

00:17:51.550 --> 00:17:53.290
is it better?

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:55.660
Is it about the
same, or is it worse

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:59.250
than the reference, the datum?

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:01.620
So you don't compare
all the alternatives

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:03.180
pairwise against each other.

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:06.590
You always compare
against the datum.

00:18:06.590 --> 00:18:08.630
Then you compute
the total scores

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:10.300
and I'll show you
this in the example,

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.110
and then there's
variations like--

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:14.300
rather than better,
equal, or worse,

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:17.066
you could go to a five-point.

00:18:17.066 --> 00:18:20.030
Much better, a little
better, or about the same.

00:18:20.030 --> 00:18:21.980
So there are some
variations on the scoring,

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:27.804
but the classic method just
uses better, the same, or worse.

00:18:27.804 --> 00:18:28.470
So here's some--

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:30.260
AUDIENCE: Excuse
me, just a question.

00:18:30.260 --> 00:18:32.157
PROFESSOR: Yeah, go ahead.

00:18:32.157 --> 00:18:33.740
AUDIENCE: Just about
the number three,

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:36.270
about generic scores
and user datum--

00:18:36.270 --> 00:18:39.496
by doing so, don't you exclude
a solution that could have,

00:18:39.496 --> 00:18:44.450
under the generic picture,
be better then others?

00:18:44.450 --> 00:18:47.219
PROFESSOR: What do you
mean by general picture?

00:18:47.219 --> 00:18:49.593
AUDIENCE: You should take all
the solution that you have,

00:18:49.593 --> 00:18:53.280
and at the end, one performs
slightly better than the other,

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:56.820
but you couldn't spot
it by using the datum?

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:57.540
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:00.100
So it's a very good question.

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:02.550
And so this is a question
of resolution right?

00:19:02.550 --> 00:19:05.150
How good is your resolution?

00:19:05.150 --> 00:19:07.380
The main purpose
of the Pugh matrix

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:11.160
is not for making the
final choice right away.

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:12.930
The main purpose
of the Pugh matrix

00:19:12.930 --> 00:19:17.750
is actually to eliminate
concepts that are--

00:19:17.750 --> 00:19:23.130
you can tell already that
they're not competitive.

00:19:23.130 --> 00:19:26.640
And you don't typically
do Pugh matrix one time

00:19:26.640 --> 00:19:28.530
and then say that's
the best one.

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:31.106
You use it, essentially,
to eliminate

00:19:31.106 --> 00:19:32.996
purely inferior solutions.

00:19:32.996 --> 00:19:33.870
Does that make sense?

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:42.500
AUDIENCE: I'm really sorry
but the video cut just

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:44.640
during your explanation.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:48.060
PROFESSOR: OK, so
let me repeat this.

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:51.930
So the purpose of
the Pugh matrix

00:19:51.930 --> 00:19:54.750
is not to select
the final concept

00:19:54.750 --> 00:19:57.120
as a result of doing
the Pugh matrix,

00:19:57.120 --> 00:20:00.510
but to identify
inferior concepts

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:02.100
to eliminate them from the set.

00:20:06.270 --> 00:20:07.790
OK?

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:08.626
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:20:08.626 --> 00:20:09.500
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:13.460
So here's a kind
of generic example

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:15.040
to explain how this works.

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:20.090
So here's our Pugh matrix,
our evaluation matrix.

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:22.820
On the rows, we
have our criteria.

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:30.680
It could be cost, performance,
resilience, effectiveness,

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:33.890
and so those are called
A, B, C, D, E, and F.

00:20:33.890 --> 00:20:36.920
So we have six criteria.

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:38.030
And then the column--

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:40.260
each column
represents a concept,

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:42.380
a design, an architecture.

00:20:42.380 --> 00:20:44.090
And so you know
we're designing--

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:46.640
I guess we're designing
beams here, or levers,

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:48.210
or something like that.

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:49.790
So this is a solid cylinder.

00:20:49.790 --> 00:20:52.220
This is a cylinder
that's hollow.

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:54.500
This is a square,
it's cross-sectioned.

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:56.646
This is a triangular
cross-section.

00:20:56.646 --> 00:20:57.770
You get the picture, right?

00:20:57.770 --> 00:21:01.010
There they're
qualitatively different.

00:21:01.010 --> 00:21:05.360
And then you note which one
is our is our reference here?

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:08.370
Which concept?

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:09.510
Number seven, right?

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:16.140
If you look at seven this
sort of shallow triangle.

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:17.520
Seven, it says datum.

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:19.040
You see that?

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:21.140
Which means that
this is our baseline,

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:23.180
our reference, our datum.

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:27.930
And then what you do is,
as you fill this in--

00:21:27.930 --> 00:21:29.360
and you can do it two ways.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:35.210
You can do-- pick, say, concept
one, the solid cylinder,

00:21:35.210 --> 00:21:39.230
and then compare it against
seven for all criteria.

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:45.650
So A, so concept one is better
than concept seven in criterion

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:47.150
A. So it gets a plus.

00:21:47.150 --> 00:21:49.820
It's also better in
B. It gets a plus.

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:55.190
It's worse in C and D, so this
is a minus compared to seven,

00:21:55.190 --> 00:21:57.040
and so forth.

00:21:57.040 --> 00:21:58.850
So the two ways of
filling it in is

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:01.820
you do concept by
concept, column-wise,

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:05.330
or you can do it row- wise.

00:22:05.330 --> 00:22:09.570
And there's some arguments
in favor of one or the other.

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:12.650
But essentially, you
fill in this matrix

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:17.390
by always comparing
against number seven.

00:22:17.390 --> 00:22:19.117
Alexis, what's your question?

00:22:19.117 --> 00:22:20.450
AUDIENCE: Yeah, just a question.

00:22:20.450 --> 00:22:22.273
Shouldn't we weight
the criteria?

00:22:22.273 --> 00:22:26.890
I mean, for example, if the
criteria A is more important,

00:22:26.890 --> 00:22:28.440
shall we put more weight on it?

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:29.610
PROFESSOR: No.

00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:30.450
No.

00:22:30.450 --> 00:22:33.600
At this point, in
the Pugh matrix,

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:35.670
the criteria are unweighted.

00:22:35.670 --> 00:22:37.410
This is very important.

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:40.900
You don't say B is
twice as important as C.

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:43.830
They're unweighted
when you first do this.

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:46.320
Eventually, when you
do the final selection,

00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:48.120
you will probably weigh them.

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:50.710
But when you first do
this, there's no weighting.

00:22:50.710 --> 00:22:52.320
They're equal.

00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:52.930
OK?

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:53.430
Yes?

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:54.395
Go ahead.

00:22:54.395 --> 00:22:56.520
AUDIENCE: Are there any
rules in picking your datum

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.230
or do you just pick arbitrarily?

00:22:58.230 --> 00:23:01.740
PROFESSOR: So I'll
get into that.

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:07.040
It should be a design that
you think is competitive,

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:10.140
that [INAUDIBLE]
maybe you know it,

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:12.110
maybe it's an existing
sort of system,

00:23:12.110 --> 00:23:16.614
there's data on it,
a known quantity.

00:23:16.614 --> 00:23:18.030
But if you don't
have if you don't

00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:20.020
have any information,
if they're all equal,

00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:22.320
then it's a random choice.

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:22.980
OK?

00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:26.670
So, then once you've
filled in this matrix--

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:29.190
so S here is for same, right?

00:23:29.190 --> 00:23:30.510
About the same.

00:23:30.510 --> 00:23:33.465
Then you essentially
sum all the pluses,

00:23:33.465 --> 00:23:36.600
you sum all the
minuses, and then

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:39.820
you have the net
result, unweighted.

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:40.320
Right?

00:23:40.320 --> 00:23:43.650
So, here you can
essentially compare

00:23:43.650 --> 00:23:47.820
that, you can see that
concept one is better in three

00:23:47.820 --> 00:23:51.900
and worse in three
than the datum.

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:57.810
You can see that concept
two is inferior in three

00:23:57.810 --> 00:24:01.180
criteria, better in two,
and the same in one.

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:03.180
But we're not actually summing.

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:04.980
We're not actually
summing at this point,

00:24:04.980 --> 00:24:07.260
because we're not
weighting these, OK?

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:11.310
But it gives you a
basis of understanding.

