00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:30.720
A negative means it's less
mature than the SP100.

00:39:30.720 --> 00:39:34.000
And at the end of
this, you can actually

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:37.620
look at the total pluses
and zeros and minuses,

00:39:37.620 --> 00:39:40.260
and then in this
case, what Brian did,

00:39:40.260 --> 00:39:42.600
he did calculate a net score.

00:39:42.600 --> 00:39:44.130
That's an unweighted score.

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:48.510
Basically, if you give
one point-- so let's

00:39:48.510 --> 00:39:50.020
look at the first one.

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:53.260
So it has four pluses, right?

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:58.240
It has four pluses, and it
has five equal to the SP100,

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:00.350
to the datum, and has two minus.

00:40:00.350 --> 00:40:03.340
So it's worse than two,
better in four criteria,

00:40:03.340 --> 00:40:04.840
and the same in five.

00:40:04.840 --> 00:40:07.630
So the net score
would be plus two,

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:11.770
because it's better
in two criteria, net.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:13.690
But it's unweighted.

00:40:13.690 --> 00:40:17.980
And so in order to
figure out what--

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:21.880
based on this net score,
so a zero net score

00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:24.600
would say it's about
equal to the datum,

00:40:24.600 --> 00:40:27.440
but it maybe in other,
different criteria.

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:30.620
But essentially
it's about the same.

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:35.080
If it's a plus two, then
it is potentially better

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:36.310
than the SP100.

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:38.230
But you don't know
that 100%, because you

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:39.640
haven't weighted the criteria.

00:40:39.640 --> 00:40:42.010
It's really used for screening.

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:47.950
So the ones that are circled
are better, essentially,

00:40:47.950 --> 00:40:49.930
than the datum.

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:51.710
And the ones that are--

00:40:51.710 --> 00:40:53.410
this is-- I'm sorry, the rank.

00:40:53.410 --> 00:40:54.970
This is the rank among the set.

00:40:54.970 --> 00:40:59.290
So if you have a one here,
you're in the rank one.

00:40:59.290 --> 00:41:03.490
And there's two architectures,
the first two are rank one.

00:41:03.490 --> 00:41:05.050
And then we have
this architecture,

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:06.370
which is ranked two.

00:41:06.370 --> 00:41:10.300
The datum itself, plus two other
architectures, are rank three.

00:41:10.300 --> 00:41:11.800
And then you see
that there's some--

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:14.260
like, for example,
this architecture here

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:15.580
is rank eight, right?

00:41:15.580 --> 00:41:17.350
So it-- why is that?

00:41:17.350 --> 00:41:20.350
Because it's not better in
any criteria than the datum.

00:41:20.350 --> 00:41:21.910
It's the same in six.

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:23.840
And it's worse in five, right?

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:26.980
So that gives you an indication
that this particular concept

00:41:26.980 --> 00:41:32.570
probably is not very attractive,
and you would eliminate that.

00:41:32.570 --> 00:41:33.640
OK?

00:41:33.640 --> 00:41:40.090
So that's essentially an
application of the Pugh matrix

00:41:40.090 --> 00:41:45.170
to a pretty real-world,
complex problem.

00:41:45.170 --> 00:41:49.150
So what the Pugh matrix is for
is essentially structured--

00:41:49.150 --> 00:41:52.060
structuring and representing
the evaluation procedure.

00:41:52.060 --> 00:41:54.130
It serves as a common visual.

00:41:54.130 --> 00:41:56.530
It provides some
amount of discipline,

00:41:56.530 --> 00:41:59.470
and helps break down
self-sealing behavior,

00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:00.520
meaning--

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:03.100
what that means is people
defending their concepts

00:42:03.100 --> 00:42:05.500
without sort of seeing
the bigger picture.

00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:07.130
Encourages teamwork.

00:42:07.130 --> 00:42:09.370
It helps you eliminate
weaker ideas,

00:42:09.370 --> 00:42:11.950
retain a set of
stronger concepts.

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:14.000
And then this is
interesting-- divergence.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.260
It helps to identify
opportunities for combination.

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:20.300
There's also a way to
use this Pugh matrix

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:22.301
methods multiple times.

00:42:22.301 --> 00:42:23.800
And the way you
would do this is you

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:27.880
would say, OK so these are the
stronger concepts here, right?

00:42:27.880 --> 00:42:30.670
The ones that do equally
well or maybe even

00:42:30.670 --> 00:42:32.550
a little better than the datum.

00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:35.200
What are the strengths and
weaknesses of each concept

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:37.210
and can we hybridize them?

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:40.330
Can we create some
hybrid concepts?

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:43.930
And so you eliminate
the weaker ones.

00:42:43.930 --> 00:42:47.770
The surviving concepts are
kept, and then maybe hybridized

00:42:47.770 --> 00:42:48.700
with each other.

00:42:48.700 --> 00:42:52.000
So you expand and create
more concepts again.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:53.560
Maybe a little
bit more detailed.

00:42:53.560 --> 00:42:56.020
And then you apply
the Pugh matrix again.

00:42:56.020 --> 00:43:00.220
So it's iterative application
of the Pugh matrix, where

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:04.570
you eliminate, you keep strong
concepts, you hybridize them,

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:06.790
and then you repeat
it two or three times.

00:43:06.790 --> 00:43:08.800
And there's actually
research on this, as well.

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:11.140
Professor Dan Frye,
who is here at MIT

00:43:11.140 --> 00:43:14.260
in mechanical engineering,
has done research on that

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:18.050
and shown that that can actually
lead to very good outcomes.

00:43:18.050 --> 00:43:19.870
So this sort of gradual--

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:23.740
so then, you don't have just
one expansion and contraction

00:43:23.740 --> 00:43:28.060
of your concept space, but it
sort of goes multiple times.

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:29.960
But eventually it does converge.

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:33.700
So this is a more refined
application of the method.

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:38.650
What Pugh matrix is not good for
is automatic decision-making,

00:43:38.650 --> 00:43:40.390
right?

00:43:40.390 --> 00:43:42.310
Completely controlling
the process.

00:43:42.310 --> 00:43:47.810
So, you know, the idea of
automating the Pugh matrix--

00:43:47.810 --> 00:43:49.660
it should not be automatic.

00:43:49.660 --> 00:43:51.460
And it's not really
done-- it's not

00:43:51.460 --> 00:43:55.100
really good for trade studies.

00:43:55.100 --> 00:43:58.460
Challenges-- [LAUGHS]
so here's some quotes.

00:43:58.460 --> 00:44:00.350
"People who have a
lot of experience

00:44:00.350 --> 00:44:02.630
exhibit an impatience.

00:44:02.630 --> 00:44:04.880
Get on with it.

00:44:04.880 --> 00:44:06.800
This procedure holds us back."

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:07.430
Right?

00:44:07.430 --> 00:44:10.160
"Strong-willed individuals
who have a lot of experience

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:13.310
and whose initial concepts
have not emerged in the final

00:44:13.310 --> 00:44:18.260
selection commence a defense
based on emotion, experience,

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:19.120
and bluster."

00:44:19.120 --> 00:44:19.620
Right?

00:44:19.620 --> 00:44:23.360
So there's this social dynamics
that gets unfolded here.

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:26.540
So, therefore, it is
recommended to do Pugh matrix

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:27.980
with a facilitator.

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:31.820
Somebody who-- similar
to brainstorming, right,

00:44:31.820 --> 00:44:33.720
where you have a facilitator.

00:44:33.720 --> 00:44:36.230
So you have a facilitator
for Pugh matrix.

00:44:36.230 --> 00:44:38.300
So somebody who controls
the flow and pace

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.910
of the session,
records the results,

00:44:40.910 --> 00:44:44.120
tries to maintain
some discipline.

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:45.890
Always compare
against the datum.

00:44:45.890 --> 00:44:50.000
I've seen Pugh matrix sessions
where you start with the datum,

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:51.770
and then by the third
or fourth concept,

00:44:51.770 --> 00:44:54.470
people are starting to
do pairwise comparisons,

00:44:54.470 --> 00:44:56.630
and the datum is sort of lost.

00:44:56.630 --> 00:44:59.210
That should not happen, right?

00:44:59.210 --> 00:45:02.450
Preventing tangents, but
encourage clarification.

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:05.000
What do we really
mean by criteria?

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:08.180
Clarification of the concepts,
and then opportunities

00:45:08.180 --> 00:45:11.760
for divergence in hybrids.

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:14.319
So the critique
of the method is--

00:45:14.319 --> 00:45:16.610
I think a lot of these things
you've already mentioned.

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:19.220
The ranking depends on
the choice of datum.

00:45:19.220 --> 00:45:20.240
The weighting.

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:21.860
You know, there's
no real weighting

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:24.390
in the classic method.

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:26.931
However, you can implement a
weighted version of the Pugh

00:45:26.931 --> 00:45:29.180
method, but then you have
to have the whole discussion

00:45:29.180 --> 00:45:33.350
about the weightings, a priori.

00:45:33.350 --> 00:45:36.500
Next, I'm going to talk about
multi-attribute utility.

00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:39.760
And so Pugh matrix and
multi-attribute utility

00:45:39.760 --> 00:45:42.010
could give you a different
rank order of alternatives.

00:45:42.010 --> 00:45:45.110
So how do you reconcile that?

00:45:45.110 --> 00:45:48.080
The most important criteria
may be intangible and missing

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:49.650
from the list.

00:45:49.650 --> 00:45:52.670
And my personal opinion on
this is that the Pugh matrix

00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:54.840
is useful and simple to use.

00:45:54.840 --> 00:45:58.700
It stimulates discussion about
the criteria, the alternatives,

00:45:58.700 --> 00:46:02.480
but it shouldn't be your only
means of concept selection.

00:46:02.480 --> 00:46:04.250
But it's usually one
of the first things

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:07.860
you should do because you
learn a lot from doing it.

00:46:07.860 --> 00:46:08.720
OK?

00:46:08.720 --> 00:46:12.920
Any questions about
matrix before I move on?

00:46:12.920 --> 00:46:14.690
Yes, Sam?

00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:16.130
AUDIENCE: Should
it always be done

00:46:16.130 --> 00:46:20.450
with a group that's working
together and discussing

00:46:20.450 --> 00:46:21.110
the concepts?

00:46:21.110 --> 00:46:24.410
Or could you also have
people individually

00:46:24.410 --> 00:46:27.170
filling them out and then
combining their results?

00:46:27.170 --> 00:46:30.650
PROFESSOR: So yeah, usually
you do it as a group

00:46:30.650 --> 00:46:33.410
because in the discussion
with the group,

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:36.140
there's a lot of
clarification that happens.

00:46:36.140 --> 00:46:40.550
Now if you do it separately,
and you firewall people

00:46:40.550 --> 00:46:43.550
from each other and have people
do this individually and then

00:46:43.550 --> 00:46:48.140
try to combine the results
later, that's actually called--

00:46:48.140 --> 00:46:52.606
that's closer to a method
called the Delphi method.

00:46:52.606 --> 00:46:54.230
Which I'm not going
to talk about here.

00:46:54.230 --> 00:46:56.490
But the Delphi
method means you're

00:46:56.490 --> 00:47:01.070
asking these kinds of
questions to experts.

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:04.520
They give you the answers, and
then you anonymize the answers

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:08.210
and reflect the combined
answers back to the group.

00:47:08.210 --> 00:47:11.720
And then you eliminate
the social dynamics,

00:47:11.720 --> 00:47:15.590
and you can see whether was
my assessment an outlier,

00:47:15.590 --> 00:47:17.690
am I close to the
center of the group?

00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:20.550
So the Delphi method
has a lot of benefits,

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:22.130
but it's not usually--

00:47:22.130 --> 00:47:24.680
you don't have
the social dynamic

00:47:24.680 --> 00:47:28.370
in the same way, which is sort
of essential to make this work.

00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:29.900
Good question though.

00:47:29.900 --> 00:47:33.510
Any questions at EPFL about
Pugh matrix before I move on?

00:47:36.688 --> 00:47:37.823
AUDIENCE: No, it's clear.

00:47:37.823 --> 00:47:38.470
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:39.970
Go ahead.

00:47:39.970 --> 00:47:44.000
AUDIENCE: It is useful to almost
have an independent group do

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.880
this, as opposed to everyone
generates their ideas

00:47:46.880 --> 00:47:52.050
and then everyone's trying
to fill out the matrix so

00:47:52.050 --> 00:47:53.510
that their idea wins.

00:47:53.510 --> 00:47:56.780
PROFESSOR: Usually not,
because if you give it

00:47:56.780 --> 00:47:59.120
to an independent
group, they'd know

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:00.410
much less about the problem.

00:48:00.410 --> 00:48:04.190
They probably weren't involved
in generating the alternatives,

00:48:04.190 --> 00:48:07.100
they weren't involved in
selecting the criteria.

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:09.380
They're probably not
as knowledgeable.

00:48:09.380 --> 00:48:13.850
And so there is an advantage
of doing it within the team.

00:48:13.850 --> 00:48:16.370
But then, you know, before
you actually go and pull

00:48:16.370 --> 00:48:18.440
the trigger on the
final-- that's the PDR.

00:48:18.440 --> 00:48:21.620
You get vetted by
independent people.

00:48:21.620 --> 00:48:24.300
That's what happens at the PDR.

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:25.325
OK.

00:48:25.325 --> 00:48:29.750
AUDIENCE: One point here is that
you can invite external people

00:48:29.750 --> 00:48:31.130
to join your discussion.

00:48:31.130 --> 00:48:32.980
So you have your design team.

00:48:32.980 --> 00:48:35.508
And it's very good to
have the experts to come,

00:48:35.508 --> 00:48:38.300
sit in the meeting, and
then give their opinion,

00:48:38.300 --> 00:48:40.264
and with the Pugh
matrix, as it's

00:48:40.264 --> 00:48:41.680
pretty straightforward
and simple,

00:48:41.680 --> 00:48:43.820
you probably shouldn't
then bias the result,

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:45.487
but you could
probably enrich it.

00:48:45.487 --> 00:48:46.820
PROFESSOR: That's a great point.

00:48:46.820 --> 00:48:48.560
I agree with that, [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:49.160
Absolutely.

00:48:49.160 --> 00:48:50.360
Yeah.

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:50.960
OK.

00:48:50.960 --> 00:48:54.860
So let's switch gears
to utility theory

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:57.080
or multi-attribute
utility theory.

00:48:57.080 --> 00:48:58.710
So what's that all about?

00:48:58.710 --> 00:49:02.870
So like I said, utility is
a very deeply rooted concept

00:49:02.870 --> 00:49:04.610
in economics.

00:49:04.610 --> 00:49:07.190
And so it's defined
as, "Utility is

00:49:07.190 --> 00:49:11.060
a measure of relative
happiness, or satisfaction,

00:49:11.060 --> 00:49:15.140
or gratification gained by
consuming different bundles

00:49:15.140 --> 00:49:16.470
of goods and services."

00:49:16.470 --> 00:49:18.470
This is sort of
economic-- very--

00:49:18.470 --> 00:49:21.560
this is how economists talk.

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:25.040
So it's-- the idea is you
want to choose a concept

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:28.220
or alternative that will
maximize your happiness,

00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:31.530
your satisfaction,
your gratification.

00:49:31.530 --> 00:49:36.620
And whenever you buy something,
when you go to Anna's Taqueria,

00:49:36.620 --> 00:49:39.500
or wherever you guys have
lunch, or at EPFL you

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:43.430
go to the Rowlock center,
and you pick from the menu,

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:46.160
you're actually doing
just that, right?

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:49.400
You have-- how much money
do I have in my pocket?

00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:52.370
How hungry am I?

00:49:52.370 --> 00:49:54.020
Am I a vegetarian or not?

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:57.440
That would filter out some
menu items right away, right?

00:49:57.440 --> 00:49:59.720
And you pick, every day.

00:49:59.720 --> 00:50:01.340
You pick your lunch.

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:03.249
Well, you're doing exactly this.

00:50:03.249 --> 00:50:05.040
You don't really know
that you're doing it,

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:09.020
but in your mind, as you're
picking from the menu,

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:10.880
and then making
your choice, you're

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:14.540
maximizing your
utility at that moment.

00:50:14.540 --> 00:50:16.410
So we do this every day.

00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:20.000
Here, in this class,
we talk about designing

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.920
complex systems.

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:25.160
So we need to do it a little
bit more deliberately,

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:28.110
but this is not just
some abstract thing.

00:50:28.110 --> 00:50:30.750
We do this every day.

00:50:30.750 --> 00:50:34.700
And so the idea is, essentially,
we have this Consumption Set

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:37.040
X, which are our
alternatives-- mutually

00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:39.080
exclusive alternatives--
and then we

00:50:39.080 --> 00:50:41.870
map that to the real scale.

00:50:41.870 --> 00:50:44.120
We rank each member of
the Consumption Set.

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:48.110
So we map the alternatives
on this utility scale.

00:50:48.110 --> 00:50:52.130
In this case, the cardinal
scale between zero and one.

00:50:52.130 --> 00:50:54.690
So, the way this
is done, in order

00:50:54.690 --> 00:51:00.060
to do the mapping from
the criteria to utility,

00:51:00.060 --> 00:51:02.190
you need these
mapping functions.

00:51:02.190 --> 00:51:04.350
And we call these
utility functions.

00:51:04.350 --> 00:51:06.180
They're called
utility functions.

00:51:06.180 --> 00:51:09.300
So basically we have--

00:51:09.300 --> 00:51:12.390
I'm going to use J here for--

00:51:12.390 --> 00:51:17.040
J means, essentially, your
attribute, your objective.

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:19.290
And then U is your utility.

00:51:19.290 --> 00:51:23.040
And so there are different
shapes of utility functions.

00:51:23.040 --> 00:51:25.750
And different scholars
call them differently.

00:51:25.750 --> 00:51:27.180
So this is Cook.

00:51:27.180 --> 00:51:30.080
He says, this is smaller is
better, or larger is better.

00:51:30.080 --> 00:51:32.940
And you see they're essentially
monotonically increasing

00:51:32.940 --> 00:51:34.770
or decreasing curves.

00:51:34.770 --> 00:51:39.450
Messac, another scholar
in multi objective design,

00:51:39.450 --> 00:51:42.570
calls this class 1S, class 2S.

00:51:42.570 --> 00:51:47.070
So what would be an
example of a smaller

00:51:47.070 --> 00:51:49.024
is better utility function?

00:51:52.260 --> 00:51:54.300
What would be an
example of that?

00:51:54.300 --> 00:51:54.800
Go ahead.

00:51:58.620 --> 00:52:01.260
AUDIENCE: An example would be
the weight of a launch vehicle.

00:52:01.260 --> 00:52:03.026
It's decreasing.

00:52:03.026 --> 00:52:04.150
PROFESSOR: The launch mass?

00:52:04.150 --> 00:52:04.560
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:52:04.560 --> 00:52:04.920
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:52:04.920 --> 00:52:05.510
Launch mass.

00:52:05.510 --> 00:52:06.720
OK.

00:52:06.720 --> 00:52:07.980
What about EPFL?

00:52:07.980 --> 00:52:09.100
Smaller is better.

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:14.780
AUDIENCE: Cost.

00:52:14.780 --> 00:52:16.120
PROFESSOR: Cost, right.

00:52:16.120 --> 00:52:19.250
So, larger is better?

00:52:27.160 --> 00:52:27.910
AUDIENCE: Revenue.

00:52:27.910 --> 00:52:29.530
PROFESSOR: Revenue.

00:52:29.530 --> 00:52:36.270
Maybe range, endurance,
reliability, right?

00:52:36.270 --> 00:52:40.020
Then there's-- the next one is
strictly concave or strictly

00:52:40.020 --> 00:52:42.660
convex, which is
nominal is better.

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:46.640
So the idea there is
there's a sweet spot, right?

00:52:46.640 --> 00:52:49.350
You want the performance
or the attribute

00:52:49.350 --> 00:52:53.160
to be a pretty specific
value, and if you

00:52:53.160 --> 00:52:58.200
deviate from that on
the up or down side then

00:52:58.200 --> 00:53:00.180
the utility decreases.

00:53:00.180 --> 00:53:03.660
So what would be
an example of that?

00:53:03.660 --> 00:53:05.310
AUDIENCE: Size of a meal.

00:53:05.310 --> 00:53:06.990
PROFESSOR: Size of a meal, OK?

00:53:06.990 --> 00:53:10.410
Well, some restaurants
may beg to differ, right?

00:53:10.410 --> 00:53:11.178
All you can eat.

00:53:11.178 --> 00:53:11.677
[LAUGHS]

00:53:11.677 --> 00:53:12.591
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
what their objective is.

00:53:12.591 --> 00:53:13.410
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:53:13.410 --> 00:53:14.310
All right.

00:53:14.310 --> 00:53:14.910
Very good.

00:53:14.910 --> 00:53:15.409
Yes, Sam?

00:53:15.409 --> 00:53:17.229
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
has to interface

00:53:17.229 --> 00:53:20.043
with something else
[INAUDIBLE] you're not

00:53:20.043 --> 00:53:22.860
[INAUDIBLE] it [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:22.860 --> 00:53:25.740
PROFESSOR: Yup, so if there
is a very specific interface

00:53:25.740 --> 00:53:26.360
condition.

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:27.090
Yeah.

00:53:27.090 --> 00:53:29.240
OK, go ahead at EPFL.

00:53:29.240 --> 00:53:32.640
Nominal is better.

00:53:32.640 --> 00:53:34.790
AUDIENCE: Like, for example,
ambient temperature.

00:53:34.790 --> 00:53:35.456
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:53:35.456 --> 00:53:37.920
So temperature-- ambient
temperature, right?

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:41.580
Humans are pretty-- we have
a fairly narrow range where

00:53:41.580 --> 00:53:43.110
we say, this is good.

00:53:43.110 --> 00:53:45.150
Now we can put on a sweater or--

00:53:45.150 --> 00:53:47.500
but it's a fairly narrow range.

00:53:47.500 --> 00:53:49.650
So, great example.

00:53:49.650 --> 00:53:52.770
Then the next one
is range is better,

00:53:52.770 --> 00:53:55.090
which is concave or convex.

00:53:55.090 --> 00:53:59.670
So this is the idea that as long
as you're within this interval,

00:53:59.670 --> 00:54:03.260
within the interval itself,
you're sort of indifferent.

00:54:03.260 --> 00:54:03.760
Right?

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:06.160
But then when you drop
outside the interval,

00:54:06.160 --> 00:54:09.280
then utility decreases
or increases.

00:54:09.280 --> 00:54:13.270
And then the last one is very
exotic-- non-monotonic utility

00:54:13.270 --> 00:54:15.520
functions that have
multiple peaks.

00:54:15.520 --> 00:54:19.340
They exist in theory, but in
practice, you almost never

00:54:19.340 --> 00:54:19.840
see them.

00:54:19.840 --> 00:54:23.290
I can't give you a good
example of multi-modal one.

00:54:23.290 --> 00:54:26.754
But in theory they do exist.

00:54:26.754 --> 00:54:29.214
AUDIENCE: Well, there
is one, and it's clearly

00:54:29.214 --> 00:54:30.805
the landing sites on a planet.

00:54:30.805 --> 00:54:32.200
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:35.260
AUDIENCE: Because you have
the one injection trajectory,

00:54:35.260 --> 00:54:38.710
and then you have the primary
sites of the primary elipse,

00:54:38.710 --> 00:54:40.480
then the secondary.

00:54:40.480 --> 00:54:45.010
And it's non-monotonic,
mostly [INAUDIBLE]..

00:54:45.010 --> 00:54:46.720
It doesn't go up, it goes down.

00:54:46.720 --> 00:54:47.790
So you have ideal.

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:49.900
Then you are out of it.

00:54:49.900 --> 00:54:51.530
Then you would land on rocks.

00:54:51.530 --> 00:54:54.160
And then you have the next
plateau, and maybe a third one,

00:54:54.160 --> 00:54:56.104
on one pass by.

00:54:56.104 --> 00:54:57.520
PROFESSOR: That's
an interesting--

00:54:57.520 --> 00:55:00.450
that's an interesting comment.

00:55:00.450 --> 00:55:03.550
I'm trying to figure out
what's the attribute-- what's

00:55:03.550 --> 00:55:05.890
the engineering attribute
that goes with that?

00:55:09.526 --> 00:55:12.550
AUDIENCE: Well, it's the
tolerance on the injection.

00:55:12.550 --> 00:55:14.550
I know that, at JPL--

00:55:14.550 --> 00:55:17.830
by the way, thanks for
organizing the [INAUDIBLE]----

00:55:17.830 --> 00:55:19.440
they made this
presentation, also,

00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:21.850
of the landing of the rovers.

00:55:21.850 --> 00:55:23.680
And they have the
primary ellipse

00:55:23.680 --> 00:55:25.180
where they try to land--

00:55:25.180 --> 00:55:29.860
well, try-- it
depends on the entry.

00:55:29.860 --> 00:55:32.800
And then they have secondary--
if they miss the entry,

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:36.042
then they have very bad option.

00:55:36.042 --> 00:55:37.500
And then, maybe a
little bit later,

00:55:37.500 --> 00:55:39.370
they maybe can land
on the next plateau,

00:55:39.370 --> 00:55:41.700
or in the next crater,
which is useful.

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:46.602
So they have this non-monotonic,
but degrading, function.

00:55:46.602 --> 00:55:47.560
The first time is best.

00:55:47.560 --> 00:55:48.808
The second would still work.

00:55:48.808 --> 00:55:51.480
But in between, there's
a part that doesn't go.

00:55:51.480 --> 00:55:53.760
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:55:53.760 --> 00:55:55.040
Got to think about that one.

00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:56.590
But that's an
interesting-- that's

00:55:56.590 --> 00:55:58.950
a pretty interesting example.

00:55:58.950 --> 00:56:03.790
So, the main point here is that
in order to calculate utility,

00:56:03.790 --> 00:56:08.440
you need a translation function
between the engineering

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:13.750
or financial attributes of
each alternative and utility.

00:56:13.750 --> 00:56:16.750
If it's not-- if it
was directly that,

00:56:16.750 --> 00:56:18.130
you'd just have a linear, right?

00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:20.470
It would be a 45
degree line, right?

00:56:20.470 --> 00:56:22.750
Or negative 45.

00:56:22.750 --> 00:56:27.040
But typically the mapping
from your attribute values

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:29.320
to the utility is non-linear.

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:30.460
And that's what this says.

00:56:33.520 --> 00:56:37.240
So then the challenge
is well, how do you

00:56:37.240 --> 00:56:38.770
get these utility functions?

00:56:38.770 --> 00:56:40.400
Where do they come from?

00:56:40.400 --> 00:56:42.890
And the answer is you've
got to do interviews,

00:56:42.890 --> 00:56:44.200
you have to survey people--

00:56:44.200 --> 00:56:47.240
the decision-makers, the
stakeholders we talked about.

00:56:47.240 --> 00:56:49.420
They're the ones who
have these utility

00:56:49.420 --> 00:56:52.520
functions in their minds,
even if they're not--

00:56:52.520 --> 00:56:55.060
So you've got to
make those explicit.

00:56:55.060 --> 00:56:56.600
So here's an example.

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:58.990
You may have three different
customers for your system.

00:56:58.990 --> 00:57:01.960
User attribute, some
performance attribute.

00:57:01.960 --> 00:57:06.610
Customer one is shown here.

00:57:06.610 --> 00:57:08.890
They need a minimum
amount of performance,

00:57:08.890 --> 00:57:11.590
but once you reach this
threshold, after that there's

00:57:11.590 --> 00:57:13.320
no more utility.

00:57:13.320 --> 00:57:16.270
But then customer two and
customer three are different.

00:57:16.270 --> 00:57:19.750
They want-- their utility
increases gradually,

00:57:19.750 --> 00:57:23.590
and in fact, customer three
doesn't see any much utility

00:57:23.590 --> 00:57:25.940
until you hit this
much higher level.

00:57:25.940 --> 00:57:28.930
So one of the challenges, then,
in designing these utility

00:57:28.930 --> 00:57:33.160
functions when you have multiple
customers is to solicit this--

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:37.180
and there's interview and survey
techniques for doing that--

00:57:37.180 --> 00:57:39.380
and then combining those.

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:41.500
And then the other
challenge in combining

00:57:41.500 --> 00:57:44.590
them is that, remember
at the system level,

00:57:44.590 --> 00:57:47.980
utility is still between
zero and one, right?

00:57:47.980 --> 00:57:51.550
So if you had, for
example, two attributes,

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:54.220
and they both give
you perfect utility,

00:57:54.220 --> 00:57:59.400
and you add them together
you'd get a utility of what?

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:01.850
You have two attributes.

00:58:01.850 --> 00:58:02.610
Two.

00:58:02.610 --> 00:58:06.690
But that can't be because the
total system utility can never

00:58:06.690 --> 00:58:08.040
be better than one.

00:58:08.040 --> 00:58:09.330
So you have to normalize.

00:58:09.330 --> 00:58:11.100
As you combine
the utilities, you

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:15.450
have to normalize them, and
actually weight them as well.

00:58:15.450 --> 00:58:19.800
So here's the equation when
you have two utilities.

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:24.030
You basically have the utility
of the system just from J1--

00:58:24.030 --> 00:58:28.470
your first attribute--
times the utility of J2.

00:58:28.470 --> 00:58:31.710
This is the mixed term,
right, the combined term.

00:58:31.710 --> 00:58:37.800
Plus the utility of just J1
plus the utility of just J2.

00:58:37.800 --> 00:58:41.910
Then you have this K factor
here-- this capital K factor--

00:58:41.910 --> 00:58:45.090
which re-normalizes
everything to zero and one.

00:58:45.090 --> 00:58:46.700
And if you have
more than two, then

00:58:46.700 --> 00:58:49.570
it becomes a matrix calculation.

00:58:49.570 --> 00:58:52.230
So it's a little tricky for
how to do this properly,

00:58:52.230 --> 00:58:54.270
but it's well-known
how to do this.

00:58:54.270 --> 00:58:58.020
So the steps in multi-attribute
utility analysis

00:58:58.020 --> 00:59:01.170
are to identify your
objectives and attributes,

00:59:01.170 --> 00:59:03.060
you develop an
interview questionnaire,

00:59:03.060 --> 00:59:05.040
you administer
that questionnaire.

00:59:05.040 --> 00:59:08.040
You then develop your
aggregate utility functions,

00:59:08.040 --> 00:59:10.440
you determine the utility
of your alternatives,

00:59:10.440 --> 00:59:13.170
and then you
analyze the results.

00:59:13.170 --> 00:59:16.210
And there is one word of
caution I want to give you,

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:18.120
which is that utility
is essentially

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:21.000
the surrogate of value,
but value often we

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:24.120
express in dollars,
in monetary terms.

00:59:24.120 --> 00:59:27.010
But utility is unit-less.

00:59:27.010 --> 00:59:31.980
So let me just comment
about utility maximization.

00:59:31.980 --> 00:59:34.025
It's very common and
generally well accepted.

00:59:36.910 --> 00:59:40.440
It's a non-linear combination
of your criteria-- your decision

00:59:40.440 --> 00:59:41.580
criteria.

00:59:41.580 --> 00:59:44.370
The downside of it is
the physical meaning

00:59:44.370 --> 00:59:48.990
is often lost, because the
engineering or customer focused

00:59:48.990 --> 00:59:50.970
attributes all get combined.

00:59:50.970 --> 00:59:54.960
So you say this system
has a utility 0.83,

00:59:54.960 --> 00:59:58.210
and this one has a utility 0.75.

00:59:58.210 --> 01:00:00.950
So one is better than the
other, but immediately you

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:02.250
want to say well why is that?

01:00:02.250 --> 01:00:03.270
What does that mean?

01:00:03.270 --> 01:00:06.360
So then you have to backtrack
and reverse engineer

01:00:06.360 --> 01:00:10.110
how those utilities
were calculated.

01:00:10.110 --> 01:00:12.510
You need to obtain a
mathematical representation

01:00:12.510 --> 01:00:14.850
for all utility functions, and--

01:00:14.850 --> 01:00:18.780
this is a probably not
just US-M centric comment,

01:00:18.780 --> 01:00:21.120
this is probably everywhere
in the world more or less--

01:00:21.120 --> 01:00:24.780
but the utility function can
vary drastically depending

01:00:24.780 --> 01:00:26.290
on the decision maker.

01:00:26.290 --> 01:00:29.340
This is a big issue in
government programs.

01:00:29.340 --> 01:00:32.770
So you guys, it's uniform
day, I guess, today.

01:00:32.770 --> 01:00:35.550
So how long is a
typical tour of duty

01:00:35.550 --> 01:00:39.000
of a program manager in the
Pentagon for a big program?

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:41.850
What would you say?

01:00:41.850 --> 01:00:44.774
AUDIENCE: It's usually
three to four years.

01:00:44.774 --> 01:00:47.190
PROFESSOR: So three to four
years, like it's written here.

01:00:47.190 --> 01:00:52.680
And what does that that mean
in practice for these utility

01:00:52.680 --> 01:00:53.960
functions and for programs?

01:01:01.090 --> 01:01:04.660
Sorry I'm putting
you on the spot here.

01:01:04.660 --> 01:01:08.320
AUDIENCE: Well,
you don't usually

01:01:08.320 --> 01:01:10.780
have a lot of overlap
between the PM.

01:01:10.780 --> 01:01:12.880
So, as one goes
out, another one's

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:17.050
coming in, so you're
losing a lot of experience,

01:01:17.050 --> 01:01:20.790
gaining somebody who doesn't
have much experience.

01:01:20.790 --> 01:01:22.322
So there's a
learning curve here.

01:01:22.322 --> 01:01:23.030
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:01:27.759 --> 01:01:28.300
That's right.

01:01:28.300 --> 01:01:30.980
What I'm getting at is--
so there's definitely that

01:01:30.980 --> 01:01:32.070
effect--

01:01:32.070 --> 01:01:34.580
but the priorities
may be different.

01:01:34.580 --> 01:01:38.620
You know, whereas the prior
program manager really valued

01:01:38.620 --> 01:01:44.410
a lot performance
or quick response,

01:01:44.410 --> 01:01:47.590
and the next program manager--
because maybe the context has

01:01:47.590 --> 01:01:48.530
changed--

01:01:48.530 --> 01:01:51.150
is very, very cost conscious.

01:01:51.150 --> 01:01:53.500
Really wants a system that
is very, very affordable,

01:01:53.500 --> 01:01:57.160
and is willing to sacrifice
performance for that.

01:01:57.160 --> 01:02:01.870
So the way you can think of
this is the shape of the utility

01:02:01.870 --> 01:02:05.820
curves for those decision
makers has now shifted,

01:02:05.820 --> 01:02:08.940
and because of that
the architecture

01:02:08.940 --> 01:02:11.620
or the choice of concept
that you would go for

01:02:11.620 --> 01:02:13.385
may be different.

01:02:13.385 --> 01:02:15.510
AUDIENCE: This happens to
NASA all the time, right?

01:02:15.510 --> 01:02:16.218
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:02:16.218 --> 01:02:18.430
And so this is not
just a DOD issue.

01:02:18.430 --> 01:02:19.690
And in commercial world.

01:02:19.690 --> 01:02:24.280
You know, a new CEO comes
in, new CTO comes in,

01:02:24.280 --> 01:02:27.580
and these utility
curves actually shift.

01:02:27.580 --> 01:02:29.440
So you've got to be
to be aware of this.

01:02:29.440 --> 01:02:32.470
So one of the big
topics there is--

01:02:32.470 --> 01:02:35.230
particularly now with NASA is--

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:38.920
how do you choose an
architecture, a concept,

01:02:38.920 --> 01:02:44.260
that is robust to changing
utilities and decision makers.

01:02:44.260 --> 01:02:46.600
So maybe you don't go
for the super duper

01:02:46.600 --> 01:02:49.540
best, most exciting,
most capable

01:02:49.540 --> 01:02:51.850
concept, but you go
for the one that's

01:02:51.850 --> 01:02:56.020
least likely to be
overturned or disrupted

01:02:56.020 --> 01:02:58.820
with the next administration.

01:02:58.820 --> 01:03:01.940
And this is a discussion--
active discussion--

01:03:01.940 --> 01:03:03.650
right now at NASA headquarters.

01:03:03.650 --> 01:03:05.450
You know, what are
the investments

01:03:05.450 --> 01:03:08.360
you can make that are
going to provide utility,

01:03:08.360 --> 01:03:12.110
even if the utility function
of the future decision makers

01:03:12.110 --> 01:03:13.440
changes?

01:03:13.440 --> 01:03:16.110
It's a big, big topic.

01:03:16.110 --> 01:03:18.260
The other thing
is, of course, this

01:03:18.260 --> 01:03:20.820
requires your formulation
of preferences.

01:03:20.820 --> 01:03:23.720
Those K factors,
those weightings,

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:26.000
a priori-- before
you've actually

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.410
scored the alternatives.

01:03:28.410 --> 01:03:28.910
All right.

01:03:28.910 --> 01:03:31.010
So the example I want
to talk you through

01:03:31.010 --> 01:03:34.700
is essentially a space tug.

01:03:34.700 --> 01:03:37.520
So we're going to do
trade space exploration.

01:03:37.520 --> 01:03:40.760
There's a trade space, a
design space, of alternatives--

01:03:40.760 --> 01:03:42.620
conceptual alternatives.

01:03:42.620 --> 01:03:44.600
And we're going to
try to understand

01:03:44.600 --> 01:03:47.220
that using utility theory.

01:03:47.220 --> 01:03:50.780
And let me explain to you
what we mean by space tug.

01:03:50.780 --> 01:03:54.230
So a space tug is essentially a
satellite that has the ability

01:03:54.230 --> 01:03:58.400
to change its orbital elements--
there are six orbital elements,

01:03:58.400 --> 01:04:01.640
semi-major axis,
eccentricity, inclination,

01:04:01.640 --> 01:04:05.830
right ascension of the
ascending node, and so forth--

01:04:05.830 --> 01:04:08.720
of a target satellite
by a predefined amount

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:12.330
without degrading its
functionality in the process.

01:04:12.330 --> 01:04:14.330
So here's a picture
of the earth.

01:04:14.330 --> 01:04:15.800
There's two orbits.

01:04:15.800 --> 01:04:19.190
The space tug is here
in the black orbit,

01:04:19.190 --> 01:04:22.530
and then our target satellite
is in the orange orbit.

01:04:22.530 --> 01:04:26.000
And so the typical
process is the space tug

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.850
waits in its parking
orbit-- the black orbit.

01:04:28.850 --> 01:04:30.170
It gets tasked.

01:04:30.170 --> 01:04:33.620
It transfers to the other
orbit, searches for the target,

01:04:33.620 --> 01:04:37.520
identifies it rendezvous and
approach, docking and capture,

01:04:37.520 --> 01:04:41.090
does an orbital transfer
and then releases the target

01:04:41.090 --> 01:04:44.510
satellite at the new
orbit, verifies its status

01:04:44.510 --> 01:04:46.670
and then either goes
directly to the next target,

01:04:46.670 --> 01:04:49.040
or returns to the parking orbit.

01:04:49.040 --> 01:04:50.630
And as you can
imagine, depending

01:04:50.630 --> 01:04:52.610
on the plane changes
that are required here

01:04:52.610 --> 01:04:54.920
this can be quite expensive.

01:04:54.920 --> 01:04:57.920
It's less expensive in
geosynchronous orbit,

01:04:57.920 --> 01:05:02.900
and there are some
capabilities that we

01:05:02.900 --> 01:05:05.420
think heard about in
the public that US

01:05:05.420 --> 01:05:08.000
and maybe other countries
have as well to do this.

01:05:11.240 --> 01:05:14.180
But there's also applications--
commercial applications for it.

01:05:14.180 --> 01:05:16.310
So, for example,
for space debris

01:05:16.310 --> 01:05:18.240
removal and things like that.

01:05:18.240 --> 01:05:21.060
So that's what we
mean by space tug.

01:05:21.060 --> 01:05:23.220
So what are the attributes?

01:05:23.220 --> 01:05:28.020
What are the-- so this is
based on a paper from 2003

01:05:28.020 --> 01:05:31.800
called Understanding the Orbital
Transfer Vehicle Trade Space.

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:37.530
And so here's three attributes
that are combined into utility:

01:05:37.530 --> 01:05:41.610
total delta V capability-- delta
V is the change in velocity.

01:05:41.610 --> 01:05:44.640
This essentially tells
you where can it go?

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:47.100
You calculate that from
essentially the rocket

01:05:47.100 --> 01:05:48.240
equation.

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:50.430
The second one is response time.

01:05:50.430 --> 01:05:53.850
How fast can it get there
after it has been tasked?

01:05:53.850 --> 01:05:55.850
And there there's a big
distinction between--

01:05:55.850 --> 01:05:58.360
it's almost binary--
between electric propulsion,

01:05:58.360 --> 01:06:02.190
which is very efficient
but slow, and then chemical

01:06:02.190 --> 01:06:03.360
propulsion.

01:06:03.360 --> 01:06:07.350
The third is the mass of
the observation or grappling

01:06:07.350 --> 01:06:08.520
equipment.

01:06:08.520 --> 01:06:12.010
And so this tells you what
it can do when it gets there.

01:06:12.010 --> 01:06:14.820
So the size of target
satellites that can be actually

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:16.140
interacted with.

01:06:16.140 --> 01:06:20.280
Those are the three attributes
that define utility,

01:06:20.280 --> 01:06:25.110
and we combine those into a
utility between zero and one.

01:06:25.110 --> 01:06:28.380
And then in this case, cost
or a surrogate for cost

01:06:28.380 --> 01:06:30.060
is kept separately.

01:06:30.060 --> 01:06:32.250
This is the vehicle
wet and dry mass.

01:06:32.250 --> 01:06:33.840
These are the cost
drivers, and this

01:06:33.840 --> 01:06:37.950
is calculated from some
simple scaling relationships.

01:06:37.950 --> 01:06:39.720
And so what we're
interested in is

01:06:39.720 --> 01:06:42.390
looking at the trade
space of utility

01:06:42.390 --> 01:06:45.990
versus cost of the system.

01:06:45.990 --> 01:06:50.720
So how is utility
defined for a space tug?

01:06:50.720 --> 01:06:58.060
So we have response time, which
is bad in electric systems.

01:06:58.060 --> 01:07:02.104
Total utility is a weighted sum,
and then we estimate the cost

01:07:02.104 --> 01:07:03.020
from wet and dry mass.

01:07:03.020 --> 01:07:06.030
So the delta V
utility is shown here.

01:07:06.030 --> 01:07:07.890
This is in terms of
meters per second.

01:07:07.890 --> 01:07:11.670
So two, four, six, eight,
10 kilometers per second.

01:07:11.670 --> 01:07:15.110
These are pretty large delta
Vs. And what's interesting

01:07:15.110 --> 01:07:20.210
is this is a larger is
better, but it's a step curve.

01:07:20.210 --> 01:07:22.700
It's not a smooth curve,
it's a step curve.

01:07:22.700 --> 01:07:23.810
Why is that?

01:07:23.810 --> 01:07:27.200
Because as you reach
certain delta Vs,

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:32.480
it enables operating just in
GEO or a LEO-GEO transfer,

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:34.710
or a LEO-GEO return.

01:07:34.710 --> 01:07:35.210
Right?

01:07:35.210 --> 01:07:38.230
So you can use the space
tug more than once,

01:07:38.230 --> 01:07:39.560
the more delta V you have.

01:07:39.560 --> 01:07:43.850
And it's a step curve because as
you hit this value of delta V,

01:07:43.850 --> 01:07:48.360
you can now operate
in a different regime.

01:07:48.360 --> 01:07:49.890
The capability.

01:07:49.890 --> 01:07:53.460
The payload mass
utility is essentially

01:07:53.460 --> 01:07:57.690
discretized between low,
medium, high, and extreme.

01:07:57.690 --> 01:07:59.490
So low is for small satellites.

01:07:59.490 --> 01:08:02.220
Medium satellites up
to one metric ton,

01:08:02.220 --> 01:08:04.500
up to three metric tons,
and then more than five

01:08:04.500 --> 01:08:07.500
metric tons, which
are the big satellites

01:08:07.500 --> 01:08:09.390
in geosynchronous orbit.

01:08:09.390 --> 01:08:13.410
And then the weighting factors
are we're going to capability

01:08:13.410 --> 01:08:17.670
30%, delta V 60%, and
the time responsiveness

01:08:17.670 --> 01:08:20.130
of the system 10%.

01:08:20.130 --> 01:08:23.100
So time responsiveness is
not that important compared

01:08:23.100 --> 01:08:24.939
to the other two.

01:08:24.939 --> 01:08:26.609
So once we have this--

01:08:26.609 --> 01:08:28.680
I'm not going to go
through all the details

01:08:28.680 --> 01:08:30.689
of the calculations.

01:08:30.689 --> 01:08:33.920
That's in that paper,
which I'll post.

01:08:33.920 --> 01:08:35.920
You get this.

01:08:35.920 --> 01:08:37.870
So this is a cloud of points.

01:08:37.870 --> 01:08:40.890
Each point here represents
a particular alternative

01:08:40.890 --> 01:08:45.090
or architecture, and we have the
cost of the system in millions

01:08:45.090 --> 01:08:45.649
of dollars.

01:08:45.649 --> 01:08:46.980
So this is not cheap.

01:08:46.980 --> 01:08:47.479
All right?

01:08:47.479 --> 01:08:50.590
This is a billion dollars,
two billion, three billion.

01:08:50.590 --> 01:08:54.359
And then we have this utility,
this dimensionless utility.

01:08:54.359 --> 01:08:56.640
And, of course, what we're
particularly interested in

01:08:56.640 --> 01:09:01.170
is this lower right corner:
high utility lower cost systems.

01:09:01.170 --> 01:09:06.990
And what we did here is to
identify some particularly

01:09:06.990 --> 01:09:08.670
interesting
architecture, as they're

01:09:08.670 --> 01:09:10.470
shown here in this space.

01:09:10.470 --> 01:09:13.290
So let me just
explain two of them.

01:09:13.290 --> 01:09:14.569
One of them, here--

01:09:14.569 --> 01:09:17.609
and we gave them names
that are recognizable.

01:09:17.609 --> 01:09:21.060
So this point here,
it's below 0.4,

01:09:21.060 --> 01:09:24.840
so it's a rather
lower utility system,

01:09:24.840 --> 01:09:28.260
but it's also
relatively affordable.

01:09:28.260 --> 01:09:31.920
We call it the bi-prop
low-earth orbit tender.

01:09:31.920 --> 01:09:34.859
So it's intended for
use in low-earth orbit

01:09:34.859 --> 01:09:38.609
and it has a dry mass
of about 680 kilograms,

01:09:38.609 --> 01:09:40.410
a wet mass of 1,400.

01:09:40.410 --> 01:09:42.240
So the difference
is propellant--

01:09:42.240 --> 01:09:44.939
about 800 kilograms
of propellant--

01:09:44.939 --> 01:09:47.800
and has reasonable
size and mass fraction.

01:09:47.800 --> 01:09:50.370
And it's fairly responsive.

01:09:50.370 --> 01:09:55.200
Another alternative is what we
call the electric geocruiser.

01:09:55.200 --> 01:09:56.860
Sounds cool, doesn't it?

01:09:56.860 --> 01:09:59.670
This is basically a space
tug that operates only

01:09:59.670 --> 01:10:01.680
in geosynchronous orbit.

01:10:01.680 --> 01:10:04.200
So you launch into
geosynchronous orbit,

01:10:04.200 --> 01:10:07.800
but once it's there
it can do a lot.

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:10.410
But it's electric,
so it's kind of slow.

01:10:10.410 --> 01:10:12.670
Seven hundred eleven
kilograms dry mass,

01:10:12.670 --> 01:10:15.530
1,100 kilograms wet mass.

01:10:15.530 --> 01:10:20.460
And it includes return of
the tug to a safe orbit.

01:10:20.460 --> 01:10:25.410
And this is sort of a versatile
space tug in the GEO belt.

01:10:25.410 --> 01:10:28.050
So that's the idea.

01:10:28.050 --> 01:10:32.140
You calculate utility,
shown on the x-axis,

01:10:32.140 --> 01:10:33.750
you have the cost of the system.

01:10:33.750 --> 01:10:35.100
You have this cloud of points.

01:10:35.100 --> 01:10:36.930
And you start
understanding what are

01:10:36.930 --> 01:10:41.760
the interesting architectures
in that trade space.

01:10:41.760 --> 01:10:43.480
This is the same trade space.

01:10:43.480 --> 01:10:45.510
But now what we've
done here is we've

01:10:45.510 --> 01:10:49.990
shown the choice of
propulsion system is critical.

01:10:49.990 --> 01:10:53.620
And what you can see here,
it's really almost impossible

01:10:53.620 --> 01:10:55.420
to get to a utility of one.

01:10:55.420 --> 01:10:57.730
It's very, very hard.

01:10:57.730 --> 01:11:02.550
And the reason for this
is the rocket equation.

01:11:02.550 --> 01:11:03.540
You see how these--

01:11:03.540 --> 01:11:08.280
so the blue are the
bi-propellant architectures.

01:11:08.280 --> 01:11:10.710
The purple are the
cryogenic, so these are

01:11:10.710 --> 01:11:13.260
[? lux ?] hydrogen propulsion.

01:11:13.260 --> 01:11:15.540
The yellow ones are the
electric propulsion system,

01:11:15.540 --> 01:11:17.610
and then we also have
nuclear propulsion, here,

01:11:17.610 --> 01:11:21.450
which clearly is challenging
and has policy implications.

01:11:21.450 --> 01:11:23.550
So you can see the
nuclear propulsion gets

01:11:23.550 --> 01:11:26.100
you close to much
higher utility,

01:11:26.100 --> 01:11:28.170
but it's also much,
much more expensive.

01:11:28.170 --> 01:11:30.300
But in all cases,
as you're trying

01:11:30.300 --> 01:11:32.460
to get more and more
utility, at some point

01:11:32.460 --> 01:11:35.470
you hit the wall because
of the rocket equation,

01:11:35.470 --> 01:11:37.040
which is very non-linear.

01:11:37.040 --> 01:11:38.730
You know, more fuel--

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:40.410
in order to carry
more fuel, you need

01:11:40.410 --> 01:11:42.840
more dry mass, more
fuel and dry mass

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:47.640
requires more fuel to push,
and the system blows up on you.

01:11:47.640 --> 01:11:49.750
And you can see this
in these curves.

01:11:49.750 --> 01:11:52.110
So you get some
physical intuition

01:11:52.110 --> 01:11:53.700
in terms of the
shape of the space.

01:11:53.700 --> 01:11:54.340
Yeah?

01:11:54.340 --> 01:11:57.574
AUDIENCE: Is there a reason
between this layering of cost?

01:11:57.574 --> 01:11:58.240
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:11:58.240 --> 01:12:02.790
They're essentially, if
I remember correctly,

01:12:02.790 --> 01:12:05.680
the capability of the system.

01:12:05.680 --> 01:12:08.160
Remember there's this
small, medium, large,

01:12:08.160 --> 01:12:11.010
you know the size of
the grappling equipment?

01:12:11.010 --> 01:12:12.690
I think that's the
tiering that you see.

01:12:12.690 --> 01:12:16.294
AUDIENCE: That doesn't
change the utility?

01:12:16.294 --> 01:12:18.460
PROFESSOR: Well, it depends
on the weighting, right?

01:12:18.460 --> 01:12:21.310
So as you change the weighting
among the attributes,

01:12:21.310 --> 01:12:22.810
that space can get scrambled.

01:12:22.810 --> 01:12:28.270
This space is valid for
that particular weighting.

01:12:28.270 --> 01:12:30.250
So any questions about--

01:12:30.250 --> 01:12:34.210
this is utility theory,
multi-attribute utility theory,

01:12:34.210 --> 01:12:38.280
applied to trade
space exploration.

01:12:38.280 --> 01:12:40.480
Any questions?

01:12:40.480 --> 01:12:40.980
Go ahead.

01:12:44.530 --> 01:12:45.775
EPFL, do you have a question?

01:12:51.830 --> 01:12:53.050
OK.

01:12:53.050 --> 01:12:57.160
So now what you see
here is implicitly,

01:12:57.160 --> 01:12:59.950
is there's nothing here
in the lower right corner.

01:12:59.950 --> 01:13:03.700
There is no system that
has perfect utility

01:13:03.700 --> 01:13:05.140
and is low cost.

01:13:05.140 --> 01:13:06.000
Right?

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:07.000
There's an empty space.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:09.880
We'd love to be here, but
there's nothing there.

01:13:09.880 --> 01:13:12.615
So the best we can do
is get close to that.

01:13:12.615 --> 01:13:14.740
And that's what I want to
talk about next, which is

01:13:14.740 --> 01:13:16.930
this concept of non-dominance.

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:18.580
So what do we mean
by non-dominance?

01:13:18.580 --> 01:13:21.760
What is a Pareto
frontier and what is

01:13:21.760 --> 01:13:23.890
multi-objective optimization?

01:13:23.890 --> 01:13:27.220
The key point about
this is that when

01:13:27.220 --> 01:13:30.520
you do non-dominance
filtering, when

01:13:30.520 --> 01:13:32.800
you look for Pareto
frontiers, you

01:13:32.800 --> 01:13:36.880
do not need to express your
preferences ahead of time.

01:13:36.880 --> 01:13:37.610
Right?

01:13:37.610 --> 01:13:41.600
So when you do you a
weighted Pugh matrix or when

01:13:41.600 --> 01:13:46.190
you do a utility theory, you
had to define ahead of time,

01:13:46.190 --> 01:13:49.640
before you did the scoring,
what's more important--

01:13:49.640 --> 01:13:53.540
fuel efficiency is twice
as important to me as cost.

01:13:53.540 --> 01:13:54.040
Right?

01:13:54.040 --> 01:13:55.760
The weighting, the
preferences had

01:13:55.760 --> 01:14:00.080
to be expressed a priori--
before you did the scoring.

01:14:00.080 --> 01:14:03.890
And there's arguments that
that's not the best thing

01:14:03.890 --> 01:14:06.950
to do, but you can do it.

01:14:06.950 --> 01:14:12.500
Here in non-dominance and
multi-objective optimization,

01:14:12.500 --> 01:14:15.200
eventually you have to
express your preferences,

01:14:15.200 --> 01:14:18.530
but you do it after
you've scored the options.

01:14:18.530 --> 01:14:21.350
That's a really
important distinction.

01:14:21.350 --> 01:14:25.000
So let me give you a little
history here on this.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.460
And what's really interesting is
there's a Lausanne connection.

01:14:28.460 --> 01:14:29.182
OK?

01:14:29.182 --> 01:14:30.640
There's a connection
with Lausanne.

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:34.780
So the word Pareto
frontier is named

01:14:34.780 --> 01:14:38.890
after a an economist,
who actually

01:14:38.890 --> 01:14:42.040
started as an engineer,
Vilfredo Pareto.

01:14:42.040 --> 01:14:47.230
He was born in Paris in
1848 and then graduated

01:14:47.230 --> 01:14:50.770
from the University
of Turin in 1870.

01:14:50.770 --> 01:14:54.220
Very much in engineering,
civil engineering,

01:14:54.220 --> 01:14:56.950
his thesis title was The
Fundamental Principles

01:14:56.950 --> 01:14:59.200
of Equilibrium and Solid Bodies.

01:14:59.200 --> 01:15:01.780
Something we take--
that's pretty basic now.

01:15:01.780 --> 01:15:06.370
Forces and torques in
equilibrium on a body.

01:15:06.370 --> 01:15:11.080
Now he worked as a civil
engineer in Florence,

01:15:11.080 --> 01:15:14.290
and then he got interested
in philosophy, politics,

01:15:14.290 --> 01:15:17.590
and economics, and he started
to think about this in terms

01:15:17.590 --> 01:15:22.850
of how does this concept of
equilibrium apply to economics?

01:15:22.850 --> 01:15:25.840
And in 1893, he actually
became a professor

01:15:25.840 --> 01:15:27.490
at the University
of Lausanne, which

01:15:27.490 --> 01:15:31.300
is located right next
to EPFL, and started

01:15:31.300 --> 01:15:37.870
applying this to economics
and societal theory.

01:15:37.870 --> 01:15:43.210
And then he did-- some of his
work was a bit controversial,

01:15:43.210 --> 01:15:45.610
but the one that I
want to talk about here

01:15:45.610 --> 01:15:48.070
is this the idea of
the Pareto optimum.

01:15:48.070 --> 01:15:51.460
And I will-- let me just
read this quote to you.

01:15:51.460 --> 01:15:54.880
"The optimum allocation of
the resources of a society

01:15:54.880 --> 01:15:57.460
is not attained,
so long as it is

01:15:57.460 --> 01:16:00.850
possible to make at least
one individual better off

01:16:00.850 --> 01:16:05.320
in his or her own estimation,
while keeping others

01:16:05.320 --> 01:16:09.620
as well off as before in
their own estimation."

01:16:09.620 --> 01:16:13.810
So what it means is if
you can make an investment

01:16:13.810 --> 01:16:19.780
or make a change in society that
makes a particular individual

01:16:19.780 --> 01:16:24.160
or group of individuals better
off in their own estimation,

01:16:24.160 --> 01:16:28.630
without having to take the
resources from another group

01:16:28.630 --> 01:16:31.860
and make them less
well-off, then you've

01:16:31.860 --> 01:16:35.129
not reached an optimal
allocation of resources.

01:16:35.129 --> 01:16:36.670
You know, if there
can be a win-win--

01:16:36.670 --> 01:16:40.080
if everybody can be better off
by making certain investments,

01:16:40.080 --> 01:16:43.560
you haven't yet found
the optimal strategy.

01:16:43.560 --> 01:16:47.610
Only when-- the only way
to make somebody better off

01:16:47.610 --> 01:16:50.670
in their own estimation than
somebody else is by taking--

01:16:50.670 --> 01:16:53.730
and this is a big political
debate still today--

01:16:53.730 --> 01:16:57.030
by taking from one group
and redistributing resources

01:16:57.030 --> 01:16:58.230
to the other.

01:16:58.230 --> 01:17:00.400
When you're in that
situation, then you

01:17:00.400 --> 01:17:03.580
are at the Pareto optimal point.

01:17:03.580 --> 01:17:04.470
OK?

01:17:04.470 --> 01:17:08.610
So that's the key
idea underlying this.

01:17:08.610 --> 01:17:16.140
So what this means
mathematically is that

01:17:16.140 --> 01:17:17.610
an optimal solution --

01:17:17.610 --> 01:17:21.540
X*-- is optimal if and only if--

01:17:24.130 --> 01:17:27.100
for a feasible solution--
so, first of all the solution

01:17:27.100 --> 01:17:28.970
has to be feasible.

01:17:28.970 --> 01:17:32.770
And this is when you
have multiple criteria.

01:17:32.770 --> 01:17:34.900
We're trying to do
vector optimization,

01:17:34.900 --> 01:17:37.660
and x must be what we call
an efficient solution,

01:17:37.660 --> 01:17:40.630
and it's efficient only
if its objective vector--

01:17:40.630 --> 01:17:44.020
J of X-- is non- dominated.

01:17:44.020 --> 01:17:48.430
And what this means is that
if you're looking at a point,

01:17:48.430 --> 01:17:51.760
it's only efficient
when it is not

01:17:51.760 --> 01:17:55.390
possible to move from that
point to another point

01:17:55.390 --> 01:18:00.740
without degrading at least
one of the other objectives.

01:18:00.740 --> 01:18:03.580
So if you can move from
a particular design point

01:18:03.580 --> 01:18:08.030
to another design point, and
all the objectives get better,

01:18:08.030 --> 01:18:09.760
you're not yet efficient.

01:18:09.760 --> 01:18:14.460
You're not yet at a
Pareto optimal point.

01:18:14.460 --> 01:18:16.950
And this gets us to the
notion of dominance.

01:18:16.950 --> 01:18:21.970
So dominance-- let's say we have
two designs, two alternatives--

01:18:21.970 --> 01:18:23.950
J1 and J2.

01:18:23.950 --> 01:18:26.110
Those are their
objective vectors.

01:18:26.110 --> 01:18:28.750
It means that-- this
is for maximization.

01:18:28.750 --> 01:18:30.640
We're trying to maximize.

01:18:30.640 --> 01:18:35.380
It means J1 dominates
J2 weakly if J1

01:18:35.380 --> 01:18:43.710
is better or equal J2, and at
least in one of the objectives,

01:18:43.710 --> 01:18:47.840
I, strictly better than J2.

01:18:47.840 --> 01:18:49.530
So you could have
two alternatives.

01:18:49.530 --> 01:18:51.830
This gets back to Pugh
matrix and the question--

01:18:51.830 --> 01:18:55.090
who asked about the ties?

01:18:55.090 --> 01:18:57.462
You did, right?

01:18:57.462 --> 01:18:58.800
It's so long ago.

01:18:58.800 --> 01:19:01.770
It's like, wait a minute, it's
like an hour ago, you know?

01:19:01.770 --> 01:19:05.430
So we have two alternatives, OK?

01:19:05.430 --> 01:19:07.300
They're all equal.

01:19:07.300 --> 01:19:09.900
They're tied in all
criteria, except for one,

