01:32:22.250 --> 01:32:23.848
Let me erase this again.

01:32:27.520 --> 01:32:31.540
Then we have these darker
red, purple points.

01:32:31.540 --> 01:32:34.770
Let me just circle
them real quick.

01:32:34.770 --> 01:32:42.000
So we have this point here, this
point, this point, this point,

01:32:42.000 --> 01:32:44.130
this one, and this one.

01:32:44.130 --> 01:32:46.980
And those are what we
call non-dominated,

01:32:46.980 --> 01:32:49.230
like we just did the filtering,
meaning there there's

01:32:49.230 --> 01:32:53.730
no other point in the set that's
better than it in all criteria.

01:32:53.730 --> 01:32:57.510
So you would consider them
as concepts to choose from.

01:32:57.510 --> 01:33:03.160
But they're not exactly
on that dashed line,

01:33:03.160 --> 01:33:05.670
which means that there
is a way to improve them.

01:33:05.670 --> 01:33:08.850
There's a way to tweak them,
to optimize them further,

01:33:08.850 --> 01:33:13.560
if you could to get them
right onto that dashed line.

01:33:13.560 --> 01:33:17.640
They're close but they're not
exactly on that dashed line.

01:33:17.640 --> 01:33:19.800
So you could tweak these
concepts to get them

01:33:19.800 --> 01:33:22.810
closer to the Pareto front.

01:33:22.810 --> 01:33:27.110
But they're still pretty good,
because they're non-dominated.

01:33:27.110 --> 01:33:31.370
And then we have those grey
points, which are shown here.

01:33:31.370 --> 01:33:33.320
There's three of them.

01:33:33.320 --> 01:33:36.062
Let me use a different
color for these.

01:33:42.230 --> 01:33:44.015
Let me use a different
color, maybe green.

01:33:49.140 --> 01:33:49.740
Here.

01:33:49.740 --> 01:33:55.890
This point, this point, and this
point, they are Pareto optimal.

01:33:55.890 --> 01:33:58.660
Meaning they're on
the Pareto front.

01:33:58.660 --> 01:34:01.600
There's no way to
improve them, such

01:34:01.600 --> 01:34:04.310
that you could make
both objectives better.

01:34:04.310 --> 01:34:04.810
Right?

01:34:04.810 --> 01:34:09.130
If you want to make J1 better,
you have to sacrifice on J2.

01:34:09.130 --> 01:34:12.280
So the only way to
modify these points

01:34:12.280 --> 01:34:15.640
is to slide along
the Pareto front,

01:34:15.640 --> 01:34:18.410
meaning you're trading
off the objectives.

01:34:18.410 --> 01:34:19.850
Do you see that?

01:34:19.850 --> 01:34:22.600
And so, in my spring
class that I teach,

01:34:22.600 --> 01:34:25.090
called Multi-disciplinary
System Optimization,

01:34:25.090 --> 01:34:26.560
we get into this pretty deeply.

01:34:26.560 --> 01:34:30.190
Like how do you
actually do this?

01:34:30.190 --> 01:34:33.600
But the point I want
you to keep for now

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:37.800
is that when you
select the concept,

01:34:37.800 --> 01:34:40.810
do not select a dominated one.

01:34:40.810 --> 01:34:42.390
Get rid of the dominated ones.

01:34:42.390 --> 01:34:43.690
Filter them out.

01:34:43.690 --> 01:34:45.880
And then you still have to
choose among the others,

01:34:45.880 --> 01:34:48.340
and that's where your
preferences come in.

01:34:48.340 --> 01:34:51.970
Right, so given the blue
and green choices here,

01:34:51.970 --> 01:34:54.520
which one are you going
to recommend at the end?

01:34:54.520 --> 01:34:59.440
And that this is sort of the
preferences between maximizing

01:34:59.440 --> 01:35:01.590
J1 and minimizing J2.

01:35:01.590 --> 01:35:04.240
That's a social
process of coming up

01:35:04.240 --> 01:35:05.680
with your preferences.

01:35:05.680 --> 01:35:08.860
But you now determine
those preferences

01:35:08.860 --> 01:35:11.515
after you've scored
all the concepts.

01:35:11.515 --> 01:35:13.420
Do you see the difference?

01:35:13.420 --> 01:35:16.720
That's pretty fundamental.

01:35:16.720 --> 01:35:17.580
OK.

01:35:17.580 --> 01:35:23.190
So, one more thing and
then we'll wrap it up.

01:35:23.190 --> 01:35:24.990
So now you've gone
through all this work.

01:35:24.990 --> 01:35:27.900
You've done your concept
generation, concept selections,

01:35:27.900 --> 01:35:32.330
scoring, and you
found the one concept

01:35:32.330 --> 01:35:35.760
that you're going
to go forward with.

01:35:35.760 --> 01:35:37.080
That's when you do PDR.

01:35:37.080 --> 01:35:38.250
So what is the PDR?

01:35:38.250 --> 01:35:39.570
The Preliminary Design Review.

01:35:39.570 --> 01:35:43.530
You explain what concept and
system architecture was chosen.

01:35:43.530 --> 01:35:48.030
You explain why it
was chosen, and you

01:35:48.030 --> 01:35:51.030
want this to be approved
as the design baseline

01:35:51.030 --> 01:35:54.540
for going forward and doing
more detailed design work.

01:35:54.540 --> 01:35:57.000
You compare it against
the rejected alternatives.

01:35:57.000 --> 01:36:00.720
Typically at the PDR, you will
spend some time on saying,

01:36:00.720 --> 01:36:03.420
these are the other
interesting concepts

01:36:03.420 --> 01:36:05.760
that almost were
selected, but we didn't

01:36:05.760 --> 01:36:08.220
because of these reasons.

01:36:08.220 --> 01:36:13.870
You show some quantitative
analysis that gives confidence,

01:36:13.870 --> 01:36:17.640
especially you want to show that
the requirements that you had

01:36:17.640 --> 01:36:20.280
defined and agreed
upon at the SRR

01:36:20.280 --> 01:36:23.890
can be satisfied by
your chosen concept.

01:36:23.890 --> 01:36:26.640
There's maybe still some
risk or some uncertainty.

01:36:26.640 --> 01:36:29.660
So any risk reduction
experiments or prototypes.

01:36:29.660 --> 01:36:32.750
So you can actually do
prototyping at this stage.

01:36:32.750 --> 01:36:34.490
You don't want to
spend too much on that,

01:36:34.490 --> 01:36:38.030
but you want to do enough of
it so you can reduce risks.

01:36:38.030 --> 01:36:40.970
And then you do a preview
of the detailed design

01:36:40.970 --> 01:36:44.700
phase between PDR leading
up to CDR. So here--

01:36:44.700 --> 01:36:47.870
I'm not going to read this--
but this is the description

01:36:47.870 --> 01:36:50.480
of what the PDR is all about.

01:36:50.480 --> 01:36:54.160
In the NASA system engineering
handbook on page 177,

01:36:54.160 --> 01:36:55.970
there's a very
detailed description

01:36:55.970 --> 01:37:00.780
of entrance criteria, exit
criteria, et cetera, et cetera.

01:37:00.780 --> 01:37:05.982
So here's a description from
a PDR from a European program,

01:37:05.982 --> 01:37:07.940
and you can see it's a
pretty big group, right?

01:37:07.940 --> 01:37:10.340
This is like 30, 40 people.

01:37:10.340 --> 01:37:15.560
And because the PDR is
such an important decision,

01:37:15.560 --> 01:37:18.320
that's when you also invite
external stakeholders.

01:37:18.320 --> 01:37:21.560
And you want to make sure that
people come away from the PDR

01:37:21.560 --> 01:37:25.070
with confidence that,
yeah, we have a good system

01:37:25.070 --> 01:37:25.920
architecture.

01:37:25.920 --> 01:37:28.650
We've picked the good
concept, and it's worthwhile

01:37:28.650 --> 01:37:30.900
now putting all this
work into getting it

01:37:30.900 --> 01:37:33.880
to a detailed design that
can actually be built.

01:37:33.880 --> 01:37:34.720
OK.

01:37:34.720 --> 01:37:39.590
Any questions about PDR, or
any experiences from PDRs

01:37:39.590 --> 01:37:41.510
that people want to share?

01:37:41.510 --> 01:37:44.004
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about the PDR.

01:37:44.004 --> 01:37:45.920
So you said there's 30
people in that picture.

01:37:45.920 --> 01:37:50.380
How do you reconcile that with
seven plus, minus two rule?

01:37:50.380 --> 01:37:53.960
PROFESSOR: Well, it's seven,
plus or minus two, squared,

01:37:53.960 --> 01:37:54.740
right?

01:37:54.740 --> 01:37:59.990
So you have a
hierarchy of people.

01:37:59.990 --> 01:38:03.044
Not everybody is a
decision maker here.

01:38:03.044 --> 01:38:03.710
AUDIENCE: I see.

01:38:03.710 --> 01:38:05.293
PROFESSOR: So you
probably have people

01:38:05.293 --> 01:38:07.670
who did some of
the thermal design,

01:38:07.670 --> 01:38:09.800
some people did
the cost modeling.

01:38:09.800 --> 01:38:13.310
So, it's a great
question actually.

01:38:13.310 --> 01:38:16.340
You want many, many
voices and people

01:38:16.340 --> 01:38:19.070
who contributed to make
sure the PDR presents

01:38:19.070 --> 01:38:21.650
all the information you have.

01:38:21.650 --> 01:38:24.620
You don't want to do a PDR
with just seven people.

01:38:24.620 --> 01:38:27.230
AUDIENCE: But I guess you could
say that in the presentation,

01:38:27.230 --> 01:38:30.590
I guess, only seven plus
or minus two, will people

01:38:30.590 --> 01:38:32.880
be driving at that
point in time.

01:38:32.880 --> 01:38:36.740
PROFESSOR: So there will
be a leadership, right?

01:38:36.740 --> 01:38:40.340
There is an
organizational issue.

01:38:40.340 --> 01:38:46.670
But the point here is
that it's a big review.

01:38:46.670 --> 01:38:47.600
It's a big milestone.

01:38:47.600 --> 01:38:49.691
Please, go ahead.

01:38:49.691 --> 01:38:53.030
AUDIENCE: The big issue here is
that all the people who are not

01:38:53.030 --> 01:38:55.650
decision makers, that
are in the picture, they

01:38:55.650 --> 01:38:57.980
will have to implement
the detailed design,

01:38:57.980 --> 01:39:01.250
so it's very important to
have them in the process.

01:39:01.250 --> 01:39:03.914
Otherwise, you have to go back
to your organization and do

01:39:03.914 --> 01:39:07.186
the PDR again to explain
the what's and the why's.

01:39:07.186 --> 01:39:10.024
This is why you try to have
these very large meetings.

01:39:10.024 --> 01:39:13.772
When you do a pre-PDR,
you do a dry-run,

01:39:13.772 --> 01:39:16.490
and you send stuff in
advance and make sure

01:39:16.490 --> 01:39:19.274
that you're really
all agreeing finally,

01:39:19.274 --> 01:39:25.453
if possible, you get the
discrepancies off the table.

01:39:25.453 --> 01:39:27.661
But then you all agree that
this is how to go forward

01:39:27.661 --> 01:39:32.580
and then the worker
bees can go and do it.

01:39:32.580 --> 01:39:35.450
PROFESSOR: Yes, that's another
reason for being inclusive.

01:39:35.450 --> 01:39:36.570
I agree with that.

01:39:36.570 --> 01:39:41.480
Any other-- who has gone through
a PDR in their prior work?

01:39:41.480 --> 01:39:42.610
Anybody want to share?

01:39:42.610 --> 01:39:44.670
Marissa.

01:39:44.670 --> 01:39:46.060
Tell us about how that went.

01:39:46.060 --> 01:39:46.750
I mean as much--

01:39:46.750 --> 01:39:49.090
I know you can't probably
we share everything but--

01:39:49.090 --> 01:39:51.850
AUDIENCE: For us, I mean, it
was a pretty big milestone.

01:39:51.850 --> 01:39:53.766
You work a lot
leading up to a PDR

01:39:53.766 --> 01:39:56.140
and then you finally have all
the really big stakeholders

01:39:56.140 --> 01:39:56.620
in the room.

01:39:56.620 --> 01:39:58.300
And a lot of them have been
involved during the design

01:39:58.300 --> 01:40:00.800
phase, but when you actually
have them all sitting there.

01:40:00.800 --> 01:40:03.270
And I think getting the
buy-in was also really--

01:40:03.270 --> 01:40:05.290
I think that's a
really big part of PDR.

01:40:05.290 --> 01:40:06.250
Like normally you're
feeling pretty

01:40:06.250 --> 01:40:08.375
confident in your designs,
but then actually making

01:40:08.375 --> 01:40:11.530
sure whoever the agency is
that you're working with,

01:40:11.530 --> 01:40:15.215
then your stakeholders are also
kind of all on the same page.

01:40:15.215 --> 01:40:16.090
It's pretty critical.

01:40:16.090 --> 01:40:18.670
PROFESSOR: Did you discover
problems or discrepancies

01:40:18.670 --> 01:40:19.570
during the PDR?

01:40:19.570 --> 01:40:20.195
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:40:20.195 --> 01:40:23.830
I definitely think-- just
generally we've had delta PDRs,

01:40:23.830 --> 01:40:25.900
if things weren't
completely thought through.

01:40:25.900 --> 01:40:27.820
Or you'd have a fair
number of action items

01:40:27.820 --> 01:40:30.840
that come out of PDR
to go and address

01:40:30.840 --> 01:40:33.770
before you really are allowed
to start moving towards CDR.

01:40:33.770 --> 01:40:34.670
PROFESSOR: Good.

01:40:34.670 --> 01:40:37.776
Any comments or experiences
with PDRs at EPFL?

01:40:45.079 --> 01:40:46.870
AUDIENCE: I did a PDR
at the European Space

01:40:46.870 --> 01:40:49.900
Agency during the
REXUS BEXUS program

01:40:49.900 --> 01:40:52.240
three years ago, and
as far as I remember

01:40:52.240 --> 01:40:56.740
it was very appreciated to bring
as many details as possible.

01:40:56.740 --> 01:41:00.520
And to be very close to
that critical design review

01:41:00.520 --> 01:41:03.710
stage in the PDR.

01:41:03.710 --> 01:41:06.590
PROFESSOR: That's interesting.

01:41:06.590 --> 01:41:09.290
So, that's good.

01:41:09.290 --> 01:41:11.850
I think there's a good to
have detail and so forth.

01:41:11.850 --> 01:41:13.400
But what's the downside?

01:41:13.400 --> 01:41:15.620
Can you think of a
negative what would

01:41:15.620 --> 01:41:22.550
be what would be not so good
about almost being a CDR right

01:41:22.550 --> 01:41:23.420
there?

01:41:23.420 --> 01:41:25.730
Can you think about
a downside to it?

01:41:29.570 --> 01:41:31.650
AUDIENCE: Probably not
taking too much time

01:41:31.650 --> 01:41:34.680
in order to clarify the
concept and the requirement

01:41:34.680 --> 01:41:40.740
because you are in a rush
to finish the product.

01:41:40.740 --> 01:41:42.710
PROFESSOR: That's a good point.

01:41:42.710 --> 01:41:44.762
So it takes more time.

01:41:44.762 --> 01:41:46.220
But what I'm thinking
about is it's

01:41:46.220 --> 01:41:49.930
very difficult to then undo
the decision or backtrack.

01:41:49.930 --> 01:41:52.850
Let's say that at the
PDR that there's some--

01:41:52.850 --> 01:41:54.950
it could be that
you really forgot

01:41:54.950 --> 01:41:56.420
something very important.

01:41:56.420 --> 01:42:00.620
And that your concept
is actually flawed.

01:42:00.620 --> 01:42:04.160
But you didn't know it as you
were working inside your team.

01:42:04.160 --> 01:42:07.820
And then if you have a design
that's almost CDR quality,

01:42:07.820 --> 01:42:09.930
it's very difficult
to undo that.

01:42:09.930 --> 01:42:12.790
So I would say that a PDR--

01:42:12.790 --> 01:42:18.020
I actually believe that at a
PDR you should have some detail,

01:42:18.020 --> 01:42:20.700
but not too much yet.

01:42:20.700 --> 01:42:25.460
I think a true PDR should be at
the system architectural level,

01:42:25.460 --> 01:42:28.970
with some detail but
not all the details.

01:42:28.970 --> 01:42:29.570
But thank you.

01:42:29.570 --> 01:42:33.110
That's a great comment.

01:42:33.110 --> 01:42:35.250
Thank you very much.

01:42:35.250 --> 01:42:37.560
So let me close it here.

01:42:37.560 --> 01:42:42.050
So in terms of concept selection
during conceptual design,

01:42:42.050 --> 01:42:45.830
we can use Pugh
matrix selection.

01:42:45.830 --> 01:42:49.130
And that's essentially
useful when we don't yet

01:42:49.130 --> 01:42:51.470
have those detailed
mathematical models.

01:42:51.470 --> 01:42:53.030
It's qualitative.

01:42:53.030 --> 01:42:56.780
And then as we move more
into preliminary design,

01:42:56.780 --> 01:43:00.740
we use utility analysis,
especially for noncommercial

01:43:00.740 --> 01:43:04.210
systems where a net present
value-- a financial--

01:43:04.210 --> 01:43:06.500
in commercial companies,
you will often

01:43:06.500 --> 01:43:10.010
do a financial analysis
as a measure of utility.

01:43:10.010 --> 01:43:12.290
And then this concept
of non-dominance

01:43:12.290 --> 01:43:13.700
is very, very important.

01:43:13.700 --> 01:43:16.550
Generating many designs
and then applying

01:43:16.550 --> 01:43:21.050
Pareto filters to try to come
down to the non-dominated set.

01:43:21.050 --> 01:43:23.940
So that's essentially
the essence of it.

01:43:23.940 --> 01:43:27.390
So I hope that was clear.

01:43:27.390 --> 01:43:30.440
A-4 will be posted later today.

